<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Report: U.S. Seeks Bargain on Russian Arms Treaty  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Clinton administration is offering to help  
Russia complete a large missile tracking radar if it agrees to 
renegotiate an arms control agreement so the United States could 
build a national missile defense system, The New York Times 
reported Sunday. Under the proposal, the United States would help 
the Russians finish their radar near Irkutsk, Siberia, the paper 
said, citing unidentified Russian and American officials. A 
nationwide defense system is prohibited by the 1972 Antiballistic 
Missile Treaty. Moscow has so far refused to alter it. 

</P>
<P>
	N.C. Declares Emergency As Irene Nears  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt declared a  
state of emergency today and officials considered evacuations as 
Hurricane Irene rumbled it way up the East Coast. Officials warned 
that it wouldn't take much rain to push rivers in the eastern part 
of the state back above flood stages. Irene's 80-mph winds also 
could threaten camper villages populated by people left homeless by 
floods from Hurricane Floyd. As of 8 p.m. EDT, the center of the 
storm was about 250 miles south of Charleston, S.C., and moving 
north near 10 mph. So far, Irene has claimed at least seven deaths. 

</P>
<P>
	Chilean Police Clash With Protesters  
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Police scattered scores of supporters of  
Gen. Augusto Pinochet on Saturday, shooting water cannon at them as 
they protested the former dictator's arrest exactly one year ago. 
Reporters saw at least six demonstrators being detained by police 
during the protest by 500 people near the British and Spanish 
embassies in Santiago's upper class Las Condes district. Police 
would not say exactly how many people they had detained. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran Rejects Friendly U.S. Talks  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Iran on Saturday rejected Washington's  
latest request for dialogue, saying friendly words were not enough 
to make up for past insults. U.S. Assistant Secretary of State 
Martin Indyk on Thursday renewed an offer for Iran and the United 
States to hold talks ``on the basis of equality and mutual 
respect.'' The aim, Indyk said, was to encourage Iran to support 
Mideast peacemaking and to stop supporting terrorism by halting the 
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombia To Begin Peace Negotiations  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Following months of delays, the  
government and leftist rebels will begin peace negotiations next 
weekend in hopes of ending Colombia's 35-year civil conflict, the 
two sides announced Saturday. The talks will begin Oct. 24 in 
Uribe, one of five southern towns that has lived under open rebel 
rule since President Andres Pastrana cleared out his troops prior 
to the ceremonial inauguration of the peace process in January. 

</P>
<P>
	No Deaths Reported in So. Cal Quake  
</P>
<P>
	JOSHUA TREE, Calif. (AP) -- A 7.0-magnitude earthquake in the  
Mojave Desert shook millions awake in three Western states early 
today, but left only a handful of injuries and no deaths. 
Californians credited location and luck for eluding catastrophe in 
the most powerful quake to hit the state since 1992. The quake 
derailed an Amtrak train and knocked out power to thousands. Up to 
90,000 utility customers lost power, mobile homes were knocked off 
pilings in the desert community of Ludlow and a highway bridge was 
cracked. 

</P>
<P>
	Yo-Yo Ma Forgets Cello in Cab  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Musician Yo-Yo Ma forgot his $2.5-million,  
266-year-old cello in the trunk of a taxi today, but police tracked 
it down at a garage in Queens in time for his evening concert. ``I 
was in such a rush, I was so exhausted, I'd given a concert at 
Carnegie Hall last night. I just forgot,'' Ma said after he got the 
instrument back. Grinning with relief, he explained that police 
used the taxi receipt to find the driver within hours. ``Luckily, 
luckily I had the receipt, so all of you, take the receipt,'' Ma 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Come Back To Beat Braves 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets avoided a sweep and saved  
their season with a 3-2 victory over the Atlanta Braves tonight in 
Game 4 of the NL Championship Series. John Olerud drove in all 
three New York runs, breaking a scoreless duel between Atlanta's 
John Smoltz and New York's Rick Reed with a solo homer in the 
sixth. The Braves still lead 3-1 in the best-of-7 series, with Game 
5 set for tomorrow afternoon at Shea Stadium. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
