<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Battle for Control of L.A. Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A fight has erupted over who is running the  
nation's second-largest school district, with the Board of 
Education insisting that a new chief executive has been brought in 
to help, not shove aside the embattled superintendent. 
</P>
<P>
	Some supporters of Superintendent Ruben Zacarias questioned  
whether the school board's action to isolate him from day-to-day 
operations was racially motivated, while the man taking on those 
responsibilities insisted that he is simply there to help. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone in the city knows that the management of Los Angeles  
Unified School District needs help. We are here to help Dr. 
Zacarias,'' Howard Miller, the district's new chief executive 
officer, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Board of Education voted 4-2 to create the  
position of CEO, give it to Miller effective immediately and have 
everyone in the school district but Zacarias report to Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	The move followed a board shakeup by voters in April and fierce  
controversy over management arising from construction of a $200 
million school on a toxic site and the possible loss of $900 
million in state bond money for 100 new schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The stakes are high: The 707-square-mile district is operating  
on a $7.4 billion budget, teaches 697,000 students, runs 790 K-12 
schools as well as 140 other types of schools and centers, and has 
67,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, dozens of parents, district employees and several  
Hispanic leaders, staged a rally in support of the superintendent. 
</P>
<P>
	``(This) is not about race, not about ethnicity. It is about  
stability. It is about process and it is about credibility,'' state 
Sen. Richard Polanco told Zacarias' supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	County Supervisor Gloria Molina said the issue was about race.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ruben is a symbol of what's going on here,'' Molina said. ``I  
think (this) is a direct attack on the Latino community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Board of Education President Genethia Hayes said Miller's  
appointment would not be rescinded. 
</P>
<P>
	The district has come under increasing criticism since it was  
discovered that the $200 million Belmont Learning Center, the 
nation's most expensive high school, was being constructed on a 
site contaminated with explosive methane and other toxic 
pollutants. 
</P>
<P>
	It was also recently discovered that the district is so far  
behind in its paperwork for building new schools that it may miss 
the deadline to qualify for $900 million in state bond money. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone was happy about the new CEO.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Mr. Miller is a lawyer and not a teacher, not an  
educator, so how can he know what's good for our kids?'' said 
Rafaela Macadamia, whose three daughters go to Toluca Lake 
Elementary School. ``When we were trying to get rid of a bad 
principal, I sent letters to Mr. Zacarias and he responded.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
