<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chernobyl May Run Until Next Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- The only working reactor at the Chernobyl  
nuclear power plant, site of the world's worst nuclear accident, 
will probably keep running until the summer of 2000, a news report 
said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision was taken ``in principle'' following a session of  
Ukraine's governmental commission on Chernobyl, held at the plant 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials pointed out at the meeting that there was enough  
nuclear fuel to operate Chernobyl's reactor No. 3 until next 
summer, the UNIAN news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Ukraine earlier pledged to close down the plant by 2000, but the  
government later said it wouldn't happen unless the former Soviet 
republic got enough money to complete two new reactors in 
compensation for power lost at Chernobyl. 
</P>
<P>
	The two new reactors, whose construction was halted after the  
1991 Soviet collapse, are more than 80 percent finished and are of 
a safer type than the reactor that exploded at Chernobyl in 1986. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
