<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Body of Abducted Kansas Girl Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAIN VALLEY, Mo. (AP) -- Cherri West made emotional appeals to  
her daughter's kidnapper and went sleepless for days after the 
10-year-old was snatched while roller skating in front of her home. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, her long vigil ended in heartbreak: Pamela Butler's  
nude body was found covered with sticks in a wooded area. The FBI 
would not disclose how the fifth-grader died or whether she had 
been sexually assaulted. 
</P>
<P>
	``For someone to come here and do this, it's just not right,''  
Ms. West said. ``She was just a little girl, she had a whole life 
ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 100 officers had searched a field and woods Friday in  
Grain Valley, about 25 miles from the girl's home in Kansas City, 
Kan. The body was found near a church where a pickup truck believed 
to have been used in the kidnapping was spotted a few hours after 
Pamela disappeared Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A suspect, Keith B. Nelson, 24, was captured Thursday after he  
was seen near the Kansas River. Police said he tried to swim away 
as officers approached. 
</P>
<P>
	The pickup truck was registered to a company formerly owned by  
David Cunningham, Nelson's boss. Cunningham said Nelson had been 
driving the truck for two weeks, the FBI said. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers, the agency quoted a coworker of Nelson's as  
saying that Nelson told him two weeks ago that he ``would like to 
kidnap a girl to rape, torture, electrocute, kill and bury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson, who underwent surgery Friday for knee and ankle injuries  
suffered in a fall after the abduction, has been charged with 
kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Hill, U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Missouri,  
said the death penalty is possible in a kidnapping case in which 
the victim dies. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are serious charges,'' he said. ``We now know there were  
serious consequences to this case, and we want to do what we think 
is appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The only comment I will make at this time is that I hope the  
public remembers it's important to allow the criminal justice 
system to proceed,'' said Nelson's lawyer, Daniel Franco. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 people on Friday filled the tiny lawn in front of  
the Butler home for an informal memorial service, adding to a 
growing mound of flowers and stuffed animals on the porch. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. West said she had braced herself for bad news.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was worried about her not eating and being cold,'' she said,  
crying. ``Now I don't have to worry about that, but this isn't the 
way it should have been.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
