<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 12:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs Win International Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Now that's more like it.  
</P>
<P>
	One night after a cold-shooting Tim Duncan and the San Antonio  
Spurs narrowly averted an unprecedented upset, the NBA champions 
captured the McDonald's Championship with a record-setting 103-68 
rout of Brazil's Vasco da Gama in Saturday's finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan led all players with 32 points and 18 rebounds and was  
named tournament MVP. He helped remove any doubt about the eventual 
outcome, and the Spurs' second-stringers produced an impressive 
fourth quarter -- outscoring the South American champions 24-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Vasco da Gama's 68 points were the lowest for a McDonald's game.  
American guard Charles Byrd led Vasco with 17 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs upped the NBA's record to 18-0 in the 12-year history  
of an event billed as the world club championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan was as responsible as any of the Spurs for the team's  
dismal semifinal performance against Italy's Varese Roosters on 
Friday, hitting just 5-of-15 shots from the field and 5-of-12 from 
the free-throw line. San Antonio trailed until midway through the 
fourth quarter before prevailing 96-86. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 7-foot, 248-pound Duncan was unstoppable Saturday before  
a quiet crowd of 10,122 at Milan's sold-out FilaForum arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Vasco da Gama tied the game 10-10 just 5:39 in as Byrd made a  
free throw awarded when the normally cool David Robinson (16 
points, seven rebounds) drew a technical for arguing a charging 
call. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when the game fell apart for the South Americans. They  
went nearly five minutes without a field goal and compounded 
matters by not getting back on defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery Johnson, who finished with 14 points and six assists, made  
two baskets to get San Antonio going, before Duncan took over. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA Finals MVP scored 10 consecutive points -- off a long  
jumper, two fastbreak layups and four free throws -- and added two 
blocks as the Spurs built a 24-10 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	At that juncture, nine minutes into the game, Duncan had  
outscored Vasco da Gama 16-10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs stretched their advantage at halftime to 56-36 as  
Duncan reached the break with 20 points and seven rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilian team's only run during the first half came at the  
start of the second quarter, when Vasco cut the deficit to 11 as 
Duncan took a much-deserved rest for the first five minutes of the 
period. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
