<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	SoCal Quake Shakes Three States  
</P>
<P>
	JOSHUA TREE, Calif. (AP) -- A magnitude-7.0 earthquake in this  
remote Southern California desert retreat shook millions awake 
early today in three states and derailed an Amtrak train, but 
caused no serious damage or injuries. The quake jolted gamblers out 
of bed in Las Vegas and shook buildings as far away as Phoenix. Up 
to 90,000 utility customers lost power, mobile homes were knocked 
off pilings in the desert community of Ludlow and a highway bridge 
was cracked. Amtrak's Southwest Chief en route from Chicago to Los 
Angeles derailed in the Mojave Desert near Ludlow, 125 miles north 
of Los Angeles. But the passenger cars remained upright. 

</P>
<P>
	Plane Rescues South Pole Doctor  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- A crew wearing frosty beards  
and red coats bid an American doctor who may have breast cancer a 
joyful goodbye today as a plane rescued her from their South Pole 
research station -- in a relatively balmy 58 degrees below zero. Dr. 
Jerri Nielsen, a 47-year-old mother of three, was inspected by 
physicians after the flight from the pole to McMurdo base on 
Antarctica's coast. She was then believed to have been flown to 
Christchurch, in southern New Zealand, to wait for a flight to the 
United States, but military and U.S National Science Foundation 
officials refused to confirm her whereabouts. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Coup Leader Cancels Speech  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistani army officers combed bank  
records and questioned travelers at airports today after the new 
military regime made economic revival and the hunt for looted 
wealth its top priorities. The search for illicit assets was the 
first act of the regime, which ousted the elected government 
Tuesday, announced emergency rule and proclaimed army chief Pervaiz 
Musharraf as the supreme leader. Musharraf canceled a promised 
television address today that was expected to outline an interim 
government. His spokesman did not say when the speech would be 
rescheduled. 

</P>
<P>
	Irene Blamed for Seven Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A hurricane watch is up along much  
of the North Carolina coast today as Hurricane Irene threatens to 
bring heavy rains and wind tonight and tomorrow. The storm, blamed 
for at least seven deaths, was expected to hug the East Coast as it 
moved north and forecasters feared it could gain strength and dump 
several inches of rain on flood-weary eastern North Carolina 
through the weekend. A hurricane watch issued today stretches north 
to Cape Hatteras, N.C. The hurricane knocked out power to more than 
a million people in Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	NAACP OKs Tourism Boycott of S.C.  
</P>
<P>
	LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) -- The NAACP's national board today approved  
a tourism boycott of South Carolina until the state removes the 
Confederate battle flag from the Statehouse dome. ``The 
ratification officially mobilizes all of our chapters and members 
to not visit or spend dollars in South Carolina until the flag is 
removed,'' said NAACP spokeswoman Sheila Douglas. More than $280 
million a year that black travelers spend in South Carolina could 
be at stake. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Troops Near Chechen Capital  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian artillery and tanks dug in atop a  
hill just outside the Chechen capital Grozny today in preparation 
for what Moscow said was the next phase in its campaign to wipe out 
insurgents. After their deepest push yet into the breakaway 
republic, Russian troops were digging in on heights overlooking the 
city, which is now well within range of Russian artillery. Col. 
Gen. Viktor Kazantsev said that his troops had finished creating a 
security zone to seal off the militants, and that a second phase 
was underway to wipe out the bases of the insurgents. 

</P>
<P>
	Gates: Watch Murdoch's Influence  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Bill Gates thinks if anyone wants to take over the  
world, it's the man who accused him of wanting to -- media tycoon 
Rupert Murdoch. In an interview with the BBC scheduled to air this 
weekend, the Microsoft Corp. chairman says: ``He's hiding behind 
me. He's your man.'' ``Someone who owns a newspaper can pick up the 
phone to the editor and say `run headlines I like,''' Gates says 
referring to Murdoch's News Corp. empire. ``What we do is create 
tools like a word processor that lets people express their ideas 
and we're not at all involved in how they choose to use it.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Kiefer, Rusedski Reach Finals  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Fifth-seeded Greg Rusedski of Britain  
defeated unseeded Roger Federer of Switzerland 6-3, 6-4 today to 
reach the finals of the $800,000 CA Trophy tennis tournament. 
Rusedski will face Germany's Nicolas Kiefer, a 7-6 (11-9), 6-4 
winner over sixth-seeded Dutchman Richard Krajicek, in tomorrow's 
finals. Kiefer, who needs to be among the top eight to make the ATP 
World Championships in Hanover in November, picked up valuable 
points by moving into the final and increasing his ranking to 
sixth. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
