<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 14:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL Playoffs Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- There was such a buzz about Saturday's pitching  
matchup between Roger Clemens and Pedro Martinez that even some of 
the players were caught up in the excitement. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I didn't have a ticket, I'd probably sneak in,'' said Red  
Sox pitcher Bret Saberhagen, who is scheduled to start Game 4 on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen knows a little bit about excitement, having started  
and won Games 3 and 7 of the 1985 World Series for the Kansas City 
Royals, becoming the youngest player to be named Series MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	He went 20-6 with a 2.87 ERA that year to win the first of two  
Cy Young Awards. He won his second in 1989 after leading the league 
with 23 wins, a 2.16 ERA, 12 complete games and 262 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	So, how does a young Saberhagen compare with Martinez and  
Clemens? 
</P>
<P>
	``Not even close,'' he said. ``I was good, but I was never that  
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CURSE OF THE BOOMER?* The Red Sox left tickets to the game for  
Toronto Blue Jays pitcher David Wells, saying they wanted to honor 
him for pitching a perfect game in '98. 
</P>
<P>
	But there might be more to it than that.  
</P>
<P>
	Wells pitched his perfect game for the Yankees and was one of  
their most popular players. After the season, though, he was traded 
to the Blue Jays for Clemens, who played 13 years in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, nicknamed ``Boomer,'' is also a Yankee history buff and a  
bit of a rebel who once pitched wearing one of Babe Ruth's caps. 
Ruth, of course, was sold by Boston to New York in 1920. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox haven't won a World Series since, and some believe  
he has put a curse on the team. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *I KNOW HOW YOU FEEL:* Yankees manager Joe Torre, who was fired  
from three previous managerial jobs, said Saturday he empathized 
with Mike Hargrove, who was fired by the Cleveland Indians on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you fire somebody, and I am speaking from experience, I  
wish the people would say we are going to make a change we are 
going to try something different, blah, blah, blah,'' Torre said 
before Game 3 of the AL championship series against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just make a change. It is just a little insulting when some of  
the reasoning comes out that we are going to the next level. I 
mean, if you are going to make a move, I mean, eight or nine years 
is a time to wait and then use that as reasoning? That is the only 
thing that bothers me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove led the Indians to five consecutive AL Central titles.  
They reached the World Series twice, but lost both times, to 
Atlanta in 1995 and Florida in '97. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was the disastrous first-round loss to the Red Sox that  
did him in. Cleveland won the first two games before allowing 44 
runs in three consecutive losses to Boston for an early exit from 
the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike keeps going to the postseason, and sometimes you get a  
little spoiled by that, and a little impatient with not going as 
far as you'd like to,'' Torre said. ``... But when you get into 
that three out of five or four out of seven, anything is liable to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE THIRD TIME'S A CHARM:* Torre said he is enjoying himself  
more now than he did last year in the playoffs, when the Yankees 
steamrolled their way to a second World Series title in three 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem: After winning 114 games in the 1998 regular season,  
anything less than a world championship would have been considered 
a failure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, this is more fun,'' Torre said. ``Last year, you sort of  
felt obligated to go to the World Series and win the World Series 
otherwise people would have downplayed what you accomplished.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
