<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aerospace Deal Exit Clause Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler has an exit clause in the deal to  
merge its aerospace unit DASA with France's Aerospatiale Matra if 
it feels the French government is interfering with business 
decisions, a German newsmagazine reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government, which held almost half of Aerospatiale  
Matra, will control half of the French-held 30 percent of the new 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler will hold 30 percent and the remaining 40  
percent is to be sold on the stock market. The new company is to be 
known as the European Aeronautic, Defense and Space Co., or EADS. 
</P>
<P>
	Der Spiegel newsmagazine said DaimlerChrysler's exit clause  
allows it to pull out after three years if it feels Paris is 
blocking job cuts or other measures required to increase efficiency 
and run the company in the most economically sensible way. 
</P>
<P>
	The French would then be required to buy out DaimlerChrysler's  
share of EADS at market value. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler representatives couldn't immediately be reached  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, signed Thursday, would create the world's  
third-biggest aerospace company. The merged German-French firm said 
it expects to win regulatory approval and begin operating by June 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the talk about the new alliance has centered on Airbus  
Industrie, and hopes that the deal would accelerate the 
privatization of the commercial jet maker to make it a better 
competitor against U.S. market leader Boeing. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will control 80 percent of Airbus once  
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace's previously announced merger with the 
Spanish aerospace company CASA is completed. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
