<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean's Mark Pinochet's Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- About 3,000 opponents of Gen. Augusto  
Pinochet beat drums and danced, marching down Santiago's main 
street Saturday to celebrate the first anniversary of the former 
dictator's arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the ailing general's followers attended a  
Catholic Mass to pray for his health and early return to Chile, the 
South American country along the southern Pacific coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The 83-year-old was arrested Oct. 16, 1998, while in London  
recuperating from back surgery. He has spent the year battling his 
extradition to Spain, where he faces torture charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet led a bloody coup in 1973 and toppled a Marxist  
president, Salvador Allende. Chile has acknowledged that 3,197 
people were killed or disappeared during Pinochet's authoritarian 
rule. 
</P>
<P>
	A British magistrate ruled last week that Pinochet can be  
extradited, but the general's lawyers planned to appeal the 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, 300 gathered at the secluded estate where Pinochet  
lives under police guard, demanding he be extradited. 
</P>
<P>
	And in Spain, 200 people celebrated Pinochet's capture with a  
cake in the form of a jail, while singing and dancing at the 
central Colon Square. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no possible going back in the judicial process  
against Pinochet,'' said Patricio Suarez, a Chilean who was 
imprisoned under Pinochet. ``He will come to Spain, where he will 
have a trial with all the guarantees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters in Chile held the ``Carnival for Justice,'' which was  
organized by leftists and human rights groups. One person wore a 
prison uniform and a mask with the face of Pinochet as he made his 
way with the procession down Santiago's Allemeda Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Viviana Diaz, president of an organization of relatives of  
dissidents who disappeared under Pinochet's rule, called his arrest 
``a sign of justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people thought something like this would be impossible.  
But it has happened, and it shows that fighting for justice pays,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The demonstrators in London sang songs, played music and read  
speeches condemning the Pinochet regime. 
</P>
<P>
	But at a Chilean armed forces chapel, retired Gen. Luis Cortes,  
a close associate of Pinochet, said during a Mass that Saturday was 
``a very sad day for all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not been able to bring my general back home,'' Cortes  
said. ``But the government has now opened the way to some hope by 
requesting Britain to release him for humanitarian reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Chile requested that Britain release the ailing  
general on the grounds that he was in no physical condition to 
endure a long extradition trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of retired military men and their families rallied at a  
Santiago theater on Friday for Pinochet's release. 
</P>
<P>
	No violence was reported during Saturday's events. The Interior  
Ministry had said police would be on alert to prevent the sort of 
violence that has occurred throughout Pinochet's confinement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
