<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baylor In the Running With 3 Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Atlanta Braves hitting coach Don Baylor could  
wind up as manager of the Milwaukee Brewers next season. Or the 
Anaheim Angels. Or maybe the Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	One place he almost certainly won't be: Atlanta.  
</P>
<P>
	Baylor, who spent six years as manager of the Colorado Rockies,  
already has interviewed for openings with the Brewers, Angels and 
Cubs. The Braves, meanwhile, are anticipating life without Baylor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said when we hired him that he wasn't going to be here more  
than a year,'' general manager John Schuerholz said before Game 4 
of the NL championship series against the Mets. ``Even though we 
signed him to a two-year contract, come on, the guy's too good. We 
were fortunate to have him for a year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor downplayed talk about his future, saying he wanted to  
enjoy the postseason with the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're getting along in the process, but I can't allow myself  
to get caught up in that,'' he said. ``This is a good run for the 
team and a good one for me, too. This is what you thirst for, the 
playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor, in an interview Friday with the Milwaukee Journal  
Sentinel, said he spoke with Milwaukee general manager Dean Taylor 
several times in recent weeks about becoming the Brewers' manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've talked about the organization itself, the type of  
players they have, what they're trying to do,'' Baylor said. ``We 
never talked about a contract, so we haven't gotten that far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor said he had a three-hour talk with Taylor in Atlanta soon  
after Taylor left as assistant GM of the Braves to take over the 
Brewers on Sept. 21. The two have spoken six or seven times since. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor denied reports of an oral agreement to manage the Chicago  
Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no agreement,'' he said. ``We made some progress. We  
have not talked about length of contract or a dollar figure 
whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schuerholz said he would not give permission to another team to  
hire Baylor while the Braves are in the playoffs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
