<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 18:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Giuliani Slipping in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Whether or not they will be able to cast a  
vote for next year's Senate race in New York, Americans are looking 
less favorably upon anticipated candidates Rudolph Giuliani and 
Hillary Rodham Clinton, according to a poll released Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The CBS News poll found that 16 percent of those questioned  
nationwide earlier this month gave Giuliani, New York City's 
Republican mayor, an ``unfavorable'' rating. Six percent found him 
unfavorable in a March 1998 poll. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Giuliani's favorable rating also rose during the same  
period, with 21 percent of respondents reporting a favorable 
impression of the mayor, up from 16 percent in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeasterners are driving the ratings dive for Giuliani, with  
24 percent reporting unfavorable impressions of him this month, up 
from 7 percent in March 1998, the poll found. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani's popularity continues to rise among Republicans, with  
29 percent reporting favorable impressions of the mayor, up from 20 
percent in March 1998. Negative ratings among Republicans grew 
seven percentage points, from 3 percent to 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Mrs. Clinton, 36 percent of those polled this month had  
unfavorable impressions of her, up from 20 percent in January 1999. 
Forty percent said they had a favorable impression of the first 
lady, down from 55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollsters found a drop in the number of women who look favorably  
on Mrs. Clinton and an increase in the number who see her 
unfavorably. Thirty-one percent of respondents this month said they 
have an unfavorable opinion of her, up from 17 percent in January 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-four percent said they have a favorable impression of Mrs.  
Clinton, down from 61 percent in January 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	With the election still more than a year away, neither Giuliani  
nor Mrs. Clinton has formally announced for the seat being vacated 
by Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oct. 3-4 telephone poll of 871 adults has a margin of error  
of 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll earlier this month of New York voters found Giuliani and  
Mrs. Clinton in a statistical dead heat. 
</P>
<P>
	That poll, released Oct. 6 from Marist College's Institute for  
Public Opinion, found the mayor favored by 46 percent of the 
state's voters, while 42 percent backed Mrs. Clinton. Other polls 
have also shown them about even. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 08:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disarray in Planned GOP Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inaugurated three weeks ago with some fanfare  
as a multimillion-dollar ad campaign, an effort by House 
Republicans to target a dozen Democrats has been plagued by 
internal squabbling and embarrassing missteps as well as a spirited 
counterattack. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, a single commercial has aired in eight districts at an  
overall cost of about $300,000, according to Republican officials. 
</P>
<P>
	In part, the effort has been slow in starting because some  
Republicans -- GOP House campaign committee chairman Tom Davis among 
them -- are lukewarm to a costly campaign more than a year before 
the election. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, though, officials in Virginia, Davis' home state,  
asked that the ad not be run as planned. In Mississippi, an ad was 
aired in which the local Democratic congressman's name was 
mispronounced. In Texas, the Democratic target successfully 
appealed to television stations not to air the commercial. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad campaign, announced by Davis last month, is designed to  
depict Democrats as raiders of the Social Security trust funds, 
willing to plunder it for other ``big government'' programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine a world where there's no punishment for a crime,'' the  
commercial begins, an announcer's ominous tones accompanied by 
menacing images and unsettling music. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercials are designed to dovetail with a Republican  
legislative strategy of passing spending bills that leave the 
Social Security surplus untouched. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans will spend ``in the millions'' of dollars airing the  
commercials, Davis told reporters Sept. 29, adding that the ads 
would air in ``upwards of a dozen'' districts. 
</P>
<P>
	While no ads have run for several days, ``We're going to do a  
new series of ads very soon,'' NRCC spokeswoman Jill Schroeder said 
Friday. She added that GOP leaders and others were being asked for 
money. ``This is really bothering the Democrats, and they're 
scared, and we've got them on the run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erik Smith, a spokesman for the Democrats, countered that  
Republicans are running ``an incredibly shrinking ad campaign. 
There's no evidence of it anywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In private meetings, according to participants who spoke on  
condition of anonymity, Davis has expressed reluctance to use 
campaign committee funds for an advertising effort more than a year 
from the election. They said Davis was pressured by the powerful 
GOP whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody was going to stampede me into doing things that  
leadership wanted to be done,'' Davis said in an interview. He said 
he ``held up the running of the ads until I was comfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the speaker's issue. I just implement,'' DeLay said in a  
separate interview, referring to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, 
R-Ill. ``He's been wanting things to go, and nothing seemed to be 
getting done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,  
provided these other details: 
</P>
<P>
	--The Republican National Committee sent word to Davis in advance  
not to request money for the ad campaign, believing the election 
was too far away. 
</P>
<P>
	--The state Republican party in Virginia appealed successfully to  
the NRCC not to air ads as planned in the district of Democratic 
Rep. Owen Pickett, who was unopposed for re-election last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In a campaign subplot, Davis is attempting to recruit state Sen.  
Ed Shrock to challenge Pickett in 2000. Shrock is a state senator 
seeking a new term in next month's legislative elections, and a 
public decision to run for Congress would be an acknowledgment he 
does not intend to serve out the new term. 
</P>
<P>
	--Two top GOP targets -- first-term Democratic Reps. Rush Holt in  
New Jersey and Joe Hoeffel of Pennsylvania -- have not had ads run 
in their districts, in what one GOP aide said was a decision to 
save money. 
</P>
<P>
	There were other problems.  
</P>
<P>
	In the district of Rep. Ronnie Shows, a Mississippi freshman,  
the congressman's name was mispronounced by the announcer: It 
rhymes with how, not show. ``People are laughing about it'' at 
home, Shows said recently. The ads were remade to correct the 
error, although the state party asked the NRCC to refrain from 
airing them to avoid interference with statewide elections next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Chet Edwards successfully appealed to stations in his Waco,  
Texas, district not to run the commercial. ``They came awfully 
close to calling me a criminal,'' Democrat Edwards said of the GOP 
attacks. ``I didn't think they were supported'' by the facts. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Republican motives were more complicated than  
Davis acknowledged in remarks to reporters last month. 
</P>
<P>
	According to GOP officials, these included an effort to stiffen  
the resolve of rank and file GOP lawmakers to support spending 
bills that avoid using Social Security funds. 
</P>
<P>
	They also included a desire to prepare ground in swing districts  
for challengers either beginning their campaigns or as yet 
unidentified. Thus, the GOP ran ads in Michigan and West Virginia, 
where Democratic retirements have created two competitive open 
seats. 
</P>
<P>
	For their part, Democrats mounted a rapid counterattack.  
</P>
<P>
	The White House and Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt branded the  
commercials -- three were prepared but only one aired thus far -- 
``the big lie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee advised  
rank-and-file lawmakers to respond aggressively. Moreover, most of 
the lawmakers targeted by the commercials voted for Republican 
``lock box'' legislation to safeguard the Social Security trust 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end, by talking about your member's record on Social  
Security, this debate will boost your member's credentials on this 
issue at a time when the public would otherwise not be paying 
attention,'' Democrats were advised in an internal memo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 22:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Pushes Diversity Acceptance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Of all the challenges the United States will  
face in the next century, by far the most important is building 
``one America out of this crazy quilt of all of us who live here,'' 
President Clinton told an Italian-American audience Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Too many people at home and abroad will enter the next  
millennium caught ``in a conflict between modern possibilities and 
primitive hatred,'' unable to grasp the fact they share ``a common 
humanity,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Solve the problem of prejudice and group hatred, Clinton said,  
``and we'll find a way to deal with all the rest of our problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton addressed the 24th annual black-tie dinner of the  
National Italian American Foundation, offering praise and thanks 
for the organization's support of his administration's ``One 
America'' initiative, which seeks to build unity out of the 
nation's rapidly increasing ethnic diversity. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation is the major Washington advocate for nearly 15  
million Italian Americans, the nation's fifth largest ethnic group. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a group, Clinton said, that has suffered from prejudice  
and discrimination in the past and is still troubled by flawed and 
faulty ethnic stereotypes. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have to do for the 21st century is to grow one country  
out of our diversity,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	And it is that very diversity, he added, ``which makes America a  
very interesting place to live in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was joined on the dais by first lady Hillary Rodham  
Clinton, who spoke of her interest in the issues of children. She 
did not mention her probable Senate race in New York state, where 
Italian-Americans are a politically potent ethnic group. 
</P>
<P>
	Guests at the bipartisan dinner included Italian Foreign  
Minister Lamberto Dini; singer Vic Damone; Supreme Court Justice 
Antonin Scalia; White House chief of staff John Podesta; and the 
actor-model known as Fabio. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
