<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Makes Offer for Debates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Presidential hopeful Steve Forbes  
offered Saturday to accept restrictions on his television 
advertisements if Republican front-runner George W. Bush would 
agree to a series of debates. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, campaigning in Seattle, immediately rejected the offer.  
``He can advertise any way he wants to advertise,'' Bush told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've made the offer that if we have this series of in-depth  
debates, in my ads I'll only use material from those debates,'' 
Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, meeting with reporters after signing copies of his new  
book, said he wants five or six lengthy debates with the Texas 
governor to flesh out what he sees as broad differences between 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes came under fire in 1996 for launching an attack on  
eventual nominee Bob Dole. Dole said the negative commercials left 
him softened for the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said worries about attack ads can be avoided if Bush  
would agree to the debates. He said he would agree to restrictions 
``if it's a series of debates, not just one. Anyone can skate 
through one debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most polls have shown Bush with a wide lead in the race for the  
GOP nomination, and he has raised far more money than any of his 
rivals. Forbes is the only candidate able to match Bush financially 
because of the publisher's personal fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seattle, Bush said debates are on the schedule.  
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Forbes has all the right'' to run negative ads, he said.  
``I just hope he understands that what he did to Senator Dole in 
1996 is going to be rejected by the Republican Party. People don't 
want that kind of campaign, where he tears people down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the Bush campaign has prepared responses to  
potential Forbes attack ads. His team made commercials attacking 
their candidate and showed them to focus groups. Coupled with Bush 
rebuttals, campaign aides said, the commercials did no harm to the 
audiences' conceptions of Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
 *AP Photo DCP101, DCW103    	
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Democrat Bill Bradley said Saturday he  
does not consider attacks by Vice President Al Gore on his party 
loyalty to be a significant issue and hears nothing about it while 
campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore hit Bradley on several fronts last week, including the  
former New Jersey senator's decision to quit the Republican-led 
Senate in 1997 and Bradley's brief refusal to rule out a challenge 
of President Clinton as an independent in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning in Iowa, where the caucuses on Jan. 24 officially  
open the run for the 2000 nomination, Bradley said he plans no 
change in his campaign tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll run his campaign, and I'll run my campaign -- which is  
another way of saying, `You fight your war, and I'll fight mine,''' 
Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would continue putting together a grass-roots  
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just proceeding steadily day-by-day, week-by-week,'' he  
said. ``We know there are 2,100 precincts where we need to 
organize, and we're going to try to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley and his wife, Ernestine, joined 8,000 people on a chilly  
Saturday for the Walk for the Cure, raising money for breast cancer 
research. Mrs. Bradley was diagnosed with breast cancer in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *AP Photos NYR101-102-103    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- To cheers of ``Run, Hillary, Run,'' probable  
Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton told the main government 
workers' union Saturday that the union movement helped make America 
an economic powerhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Clinton said there is still work to do. ``As proud as I  
am of the economy, it hasn't reached everyone,'' she told members 
of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal 
Employees. ``We have to work to make sure upstate and some areas in 
the city receive the full benefits of this economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Citing the commitment to labor laws of her husband, President  
Clinton, and his administration, Mrs. Clinton said she is ``very 
proud'' of what she said the Clinton White House's partnership with 
labor has accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Mrs. Clinton has not officially announced her candidacy  
for the Senate seat being vacated by retiring New York Democrat 
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, it is widely believed she will run. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Presidential aspirant Pat Buchanan gained his  
first foothold in Iowa's Reform Party, seating more than half the 
delegates to the party's annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, principally Connecticut and New Hampshire, efforts by  
Buchanan delegates to seat themselves in Reform conventions have 
met resistance. Signs of tension were in evidence Saturday between 
Buchanan's supporters and more established party members, but both 
sides promised to cooperate to their mutual advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's welcome,'' said Jim Hennager, last year's Reform  
Party candidate for Iowa governor. ``I don't think we're going to 
have any serious problem in that regard. We're looking forward to 
new people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan remains a candidate for the Republican Party nomination  
but has expressed interest in bolting to seek the White House under 
the Reform banner. Resistance to that has come from backers of 
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, the party's highest elected official. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Cormack, a GOP state legislator from Fort Dodge, leader  
of a Buchanan steering committee, said the Reform Party and the 
Buchanan campaign comprise ``a very similar makeup of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reform officials would not release precise delegate numbers  
Saturday. But a head count showed 80 people in the convention room, 
and Cormack claimed 50 were Buchanan backers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Medicare reform should be led by medical  
experts, not politicians, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate, making campaign stops at  
long-term-care facilities in four Iowa cities, guaranteed that 
benefits will not be cut for current enrollees or for those almost 
eligible for Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal Hatch calls his Agenda for Senior Health Care also  
includes increased access to long-term care, established standards 
for long-term-care insurance policies and increased tax incentives 
for purchase policies. 
  	   	
</P>
