<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No.2 Penn St 23, No. 18 Ohio St. 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Don't talk, play football paid off for  
No. 2 Penn State on Saturday as Eric McCoo slipped enough tackles 
to gain a career-best 211 yards and set up 10 points in leading the 
Nittany Lions to a 23-10 victory over No. 18 Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State remained perfect through seven games and gave Joe  
Paterno his 314th career victory, tying him for third place with 
Amos Alonzo Stagg for most among major college coaches. Bear Bryant 
has 323, and Pop Warner 319. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying his players have been besieged by fans and reporters all  
season, Paterno cut off most interviews this week in a rare policy 
change. The 72-year-old Paterno's edict came just after Ohio State 
coach John Cooper said if both teams played their best, the Lions 
would win, a remark that upset most Buckeyes players. 
</P>
<P>
	Paterno can thank McCoo and an inspired defense led by  
linebacker LaVar Arrington for playing their best. The Nittany 
Lions (7-0, 3-0 Big Ten) had two field goals blocked, fumbled in 
the end zone for a Buckeyes TD and had trouble scoring from inside 
the Ohio State 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State (4-3, 1-2) was outplayed from the start as the Lions  
held the Buckeyes to just 143 yards while piling up 422. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Bellisari was sacked eight times -- Arrington had 2 1/2 after  
entering the game with one all season -- and completed just seven of 
21 passes for 78 yards with an interception. 
</P>
<P>
	It was this bad for Bellisari: He missed a play near the end of  
the game after taking a vicious hit to the upper chest from 
Arrington with 2:23 left. 
</P>
<P>
	McCoo, a 5-10, 201-pound sophomore, carried nine times for 121  
yards in the first half as the Nittany Lions took a 13-10 lead at 
intermission. He finished with 22 carries for 211 yards, and also 
caught four passes for 47 yards. Last season, McCoo ran for 206 
yards against Michigan State. 
</P>
<P>
	With Rashard Casey running the offense in the second half, Penn  
State scored on its first possession to take a 20-10 lead. Casey, 
who has alternated with Kevin Thompson all year, capped a 
seven-play, 62-yard drive with a 5-yard TD run on a perfectly 
executed bootleg, faking two handoffs, putting the ball on his hip 
and rolling left past a baffled Buckeyes defense. Casey was 
11-of-15 for 109 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Forney added his third field goal of the game, a  
28-yarder early in the fourth quarter, to give the Lions their 
ninth consecutive victory, second-longest in the nation behind 
Marshall's 10 in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss not only dropped Ohio State out of the big bowl  
picture, but probably also ended their chances for a Big Ten title. 
The Buckeyes, who haven't lost four games in a season since 1994, 
have games remaining against nationally ranked Michigan State and 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nittany Lions, looking for their first national title since  
1986, have tough games left against Purdue next Saturday, Michigan 
and at Michigan State. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State led 13-3 with 3:40 left in the half, but was backed  
up to its own 6 when Thompson was slammed from behind by linebacker 
Na'il Diggs and fumbled, with free safety Gary Berry recovering in 
the end zone for a touchdown. Thompson injured his right shoulder 
on the play and sat out the rest of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions wasted little time moving to a 7-0 lead as the Beaver  
Stadium crowd of 97,007 roared. Thompson hit McCoo with a 20-yard 
pass to open the game, and then McCoo slipped two would-be tacklers 
with nifty inside cuts and ran 53 yards to the Ohio State 7. Two 
plays later, Thompson hit fullback Mike Cerimele with a 6-yard 
scoring pass just 1:35 into the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense took over when Ohio State got the ball. Bellisari  
fumbled when sacked by end Courtney Brown for a 13-yard loss and 
linebacker Brandon Short recovered at the Buckeyes 19. Ohio State 
held and then linebacker Jason Ott blocked Forney's 39-yard field 
goal attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Stultz kicked a 47-yard field goal midway through the  
quarter, but the Lions, who outgained the Buckeyes 238-71 in the 
first half, made it 10-3 on Forney's 38-yard field goal four plays 
after holder Matt Senneca ran 10 yards for first down on a fake 
field goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Forney kicked a 39-yard field goal with 6:49 left in the half  
before the Buckeyes scored on Berry's fumble recovery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 06:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aerospace Deal Exit Clause Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler has an exit clause in the deal to  
merge its aerospace unit DASA with France's Aerospatiale Matra if 
it feels the French government is interfering with business 
decisions, a German newsmagazine reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government, which held almost half of Aerospatiale  
Matra, will control half of the French-held 30 percent of the new 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler will hold 30 percent and the remaining 40  
percent is to be sold on the stock market. The new company is to be 
known as the European Aeronautic, Defense and Space Co., or EADS. 
</P>
<P>
	Der Spiegel newsmagazine said DaimlerChrysler's exit clause  
allows it to pull out after three years if it feels Paris is 
blocking job cuts or other measures required to increase efficiency 
and run the company in the most economically sensible way. 
</P>
<P>
	The French would then be required to buy out DaimlerChrysler's  
share of EADS at market value. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler representatives couldn't immediately be reached  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, signed Thursday, would create the world's  
third-biggest aerospace company. The merged German-French firm said 
it expects to win regulatory approval and begin operating by June 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the talk about the new alliance has centered on Airbus  
Industrie, and hopes that the deal would accelerate the 
privatization of the commercial jet maker to make it a better 
competitor against U.S. market leader Boeing. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will control 80 percent of Airbus once  
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace's previously announced merger with the 
Spanish aerospace company CASA is completed. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 14:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Website Logs Earthquake Anecdotes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In case of earthquake: duck, cover and log  
on. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a few hours of Saturday's magnitude-7.0 quake in the  
Southern California desert, more than 10,000 people ventured into 
cyberspace to register their experiences on a new Website 
(www-socal.wr.usgs.gov) run by the U.S. Geological Survey. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you feel it?'' the site asks.  
</P>
<P>
	Scientists will use the thousands of anecdotal reports to  
determine whether they were right about the regions expected to 
suffer the worst shaking, USGS seismologist Mary Lou Zoback said. 
Though not conclusive, the results offer another way to gauge 
research on the mysterious mechanics of earthquakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The online participants answer a host of questions, including:  
Were they inside or outside when the quake hit? Was it difficult to 
stand or walk? And what type of damage did their home sustain? 
</P>
<P>
	The responses are categorized by ZIP code. All other  
identification is voluntary, Ms. Zoback said. 
</P>
<P>
	A common assumption is that earthquake tremors radiate outward  
like ripples in a pool of water. In fact, the conditions of the 
ground can focus shock waves and bounce them around below the 
surface, hitting some areas harder than others, Ms. Zoback said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2-month-old Internet site, known as the Community Internet  
Intensity Map, uses the experiences of residents to place ZIP codes 
in a 12-level ranking system, which ranges from ``Not Felt'' to 
``Extreme.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers will use the stories to augment scientific data  
about areas that may require stronger structures and roadways to 
prepare for future quakes, Ms. Zoback said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 17:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No.20 Purdue 52, No.5 Mich. St. 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- Purdue found a route for success  
against Michigan State's top-ranked rushing defense -- Drew Brees to 
Chris Daniels. 
</P>
<P>
	Brees threw five touchdown passes in the first half, including  
three to Daniels, and ran for one in the second half as No. 20 
Purdue ended No. 5 Michigan State's perfect season 52-28 Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue (5-2, 2-2 Big Ten) built a 35-14 lead by halftime as  
Brees completed 23-of-33 for 344 yards. Daniels had 12 catches in 
the first half for 200 yards, with TD receptions of 51, 10 and 4 
yards. Brees finished with a season-high 509 yards, hitting 
40-of-57. His career high is 522, set against Wisconsin last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniels, who went into the game leading the Big Ten with 57  
receptions, set Big Ten records with 301 receiving yards and 21 
catches. The old record for receiving yards was 285 by Thomas Lewis 
of Indiana in 1993 and Purdue's Randall Lane, who caught one of 
Brees' TD passes Saturday, set the reception record of 18 last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State (6-1, 3-1) scored first on an 18-yard TD pass  
from Bill Burke to Plaxico Burress. The Boilermakers, coming off 
consecutive road losses to Michigan and Ohio State, responded with 
three touchdowns in the opening quarter and built their lead to 
28-6 on a 7-yard pass from Brees to Lane with 12:46 left in the 
first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State, which came into the game allowing an average of  
36.7 rushing yards a game, surrendered 35 in the first half and 59 
for the game. Michigan State, which had Burke sacked four times in 
the first half for minus-34 yards, netted only 5 yards in the first 
two quarters and 44 for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boilermakers pulled away with three TDs in about six minutes  
with the help of two turnovers. Trailing 6-0 after Paul Edinger's 
extra point hit the goal post, the Boilermakers went 69 yards in 
five plays to score on a 51-yard pass play to Daniels, who got 
behind cornerback Amp Campbell and took the pass in stride. Travis 
Dorsch kicked the first of five extra points to put Purdue ahead 
for good with 8:40 remaining in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	On Michigan State's first play following the kickoff, Burress  
fumbled when hit by Mike Hawthorne and Mike Rose recovered for the 
Boilermakers at the Spartans 27. Vinny Sutherland, who threw an 
incomplete pass on first down, then caught a 27-yard TD pass from 
Brees with 8:14 left in the period. 
</P>
<P>
	Adrian Beasley intercepted Burke's pass at the Purdue 39 and  
returned it to the Michigan State 49. Eight plays later, Brees and 
Daniels connected on a 10-yard scoring pass. Brees completed all 
four of his pass attempts on the drive and also had a 10-yard run. 
</P>
<P>
	Two long returns of pass interceptions helped bring the Spartans  
back into the game. T.J. Turner brought the first back 88 yards in 
the second quarter and Michigan State cut its deficit to 35-28 when 
Brees threw into double coverage and Aric Morris brought it back 76 
yards for a touchdown with 4:14 left in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue responded with a seven-play, 74-yard drive that ended  
when Brees raced to his right and stretched into the end zone on a 
1-yard run. Brees completed five passes on the drive with Daniels 
gaining 60 yards on three catches. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State had another chance to draw closer following its  
fourth interception off Brees in the fourth quarter. But the drive 
ended with Beasley's goal-line interception and 40-yard return. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boilermakers made it 45-28 on a 23-yard field by Dorsch with  
3:19 to play and David Nugent's 12-yard fumble return for a 
touchdown 18 seconds later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
