<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Peace Talks To Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Following months of delays, the  
government and leftist rebels will begin peace negotiations next 
weekend in hopes of ending Colombia's 35-year civil conflict, the 
two sides announced Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks will begin Oct. 24 in Uribe, one of five southern  
towns that has lived under open rebel rule since President Andres 
Pastrana cleared out his troops prior to the ceremonial 
inauguration of the peace process in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Citizen peace groups have set the same date for nationwide  
marches to demand a cease-fire, an end to violence against 
civilians, and the initiation of formal talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict has claimed at least 30,000 lives, and fighting has  
raged unabated despite renewed peace efforts since Pastrana took 
office last year. 
</P>
<P>
	After reaching a sweeping negotiating agenda in May, the  
government and the rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or 
FARC, hit a deadlock. Pastrana refused to proceed unless the 
15,000-member insurgency allowed an international commission to 
monitor its activities in the Switzerland-sized demilitarized zone. 
</P>
<P>
	The FARC refused, however, prompting the government to go ahead  
with the talks without international verifiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Skeptical of the rebels' professed desire for peace, U.S.  
officials have criticized Pastrana's decision while stepping up 
police and military aid to the Andean nation. Pastrana was in 
Washington recently to request hundreds of millions of dollars in 
aid to strengthen his hand on the battlefield and at the peace 
table. 
</P>
<P>
	In their joint statement Saturday, the government and FARC said  
they were ready to begin discussions on reforms to attack the 
country's endemic poverty and political corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	The venue for the talks, Uribe, was the FARC's longtime command  
center before a 1991 military offensive drove out the peasant-based 
insurgents. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
