<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 12:18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glance at Earthquake Magnitudes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While no serious damage has been reported from today's Southern  
California earthquake, its preliminary magnitude -- 7.0 -- was more 
than strong enough to bring major destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Earthquake magnitudes are measures of earthquake size calculated  
from ground motion recorded on seismographs. With each scale, an 
increase in one full number -- from 6.5 to 7.5, for example -- means 
the quake's magnitude is 10 times as great. 
</P>
<P>
	There is theoretically no top limit to the scale, but a  
magnitude 8 is considered to be capable of tremendous damage. On 
Sept. 19, 1985, a magnitude 8.1 earthquake in Mexico left 9,500 
people dead. 
</P>
<P>
	A magnitude 7 quake brings the potential of widespread damage.  
On Oct. 17, 1989, the Loma Prieta earthquake in Northern California 
killed 67 people and caused an estimated $6 billion in damage. It 
was a 7.1 magnitude. 
</P>
<P>
	While technically less severe, magnitude 6 quakes have sometimes  
proven more devastating in California. Southern California's last 
serious brush with such a quake was on Jan. 14, 1994, when a 
magnitude 6.7 quake struck Northridge, just north of Los Angeles, 
killing 72 people and causing an estimated $40 billion in damage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 16:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
