<DOCNO> APW19991016.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 08:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boom Transforms Middletown USA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) -- The change shows in Art Emmerling's hands.  
</P>
<P>
	They're cleaner, softer and free of the blisters he earned in  
the profane din of Muncie's General Motors plant. The former 
factory worker is now chief programmer for an employer that went 
from silverware to software. ``I do more with the mind now,'' 
Emmerling says. 
</P>
<P>
	Here between Wall Street and Silicon Valley, America's  
extraordinary economic boom has transformed its most famously 
ordinary town. Muncie has been known as Middletown, USA, since 
1929, when two sociologists made it the setting for a book on the 
habits of typical Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	But what is typical in American economics has changed, and so  
has Muncie. ``The deindustrialization of Muncie is just about 
complete,'' says Bruce Geelhoed, who chronicles the city's 
evolution as director of the Center for Middletown Studies at Ball 
State University in Muncie. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment has reached historical lows, income has hit new  
highs. A prospering symphony recently drew the famed Marvin 
Hamlisch as guest director, and diners are paying $30 for tournedos 
a la Newburg at Foxfires. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers in this former rust-belt city have followed its move  
from manufacturing to service. Jobs in retailing overtook those in 
manufacturing in 1982, and service positions overtook manufacturing 
in 1989. The city built on Ball glass jars and Corvette 
transmissions now churns out professionals like Emmerling. 
</P>
<P>
	Emmerling's employer, Ontario Systems, is the fastest-growing  
division of Ontario Corp., a 40-year-old manufacturer that once 
made silverware and jet parts. Now it makes semiconductor equipment 
and debt-collection software. 
</P>
<P>
	Across town, another former manufacturing worker also prospers  
as a service professional. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Johnson retired in February from Borg-Warner Automotive to  
expand a side business in designing custom homes. As home buyers 
took advantage of falling interest rates, Johnson went from 
designing 100 homes in 1990 to 180 last year, at $300 to $3,000 
apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the housing market was on its back, I probably would have  
toughed it out'' at the plant, says Johnson, 54. ``Now,'' he adds 
with a smile, ``I'm able to do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's not alone in finding enough work. Muncie is the seat of  
Delaware County, where unemployment -- which peaked at 16.6 percent 
in 1983 -- is now at 2.7 percent. Per capita income rose from 
$15,001 in 1989 to $21,504 in 1997. The city has paced both the 
nation and the state, where family income rose 13 percent to 
$53,581 between 1994 and 1997, just $231 above the national figure. 
</P>
<P>
	That hasn't turned Main Street into Rodeo Drive, but there are  
signs of creeping affluence. Until last year a handful of local 
gourmands were quick to recommend Foxfires, the restaurant owned by 
``Garfield'' cartoonist Jim Davis. The tony bistro now faces stiff 
competition from Benjamin's, where stuffed veal goes for $23.96, 
and Lucy Lucy, where diners pay $22 for the 18-ounce ``cowboy 
steak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People are taking time to enjoy life a little more,'' says Dan  
Allen, a former GM plant manager who now heads the Chamber of 
Commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Economics are also changing the look of the city. Downtown, on a  
recent Monday, a pigeon perched on an unused billiard table in the 
window of Doc's. Another window promised: ``Opening soon.'' Across 
the street, where Kelso Inc. Educational Materials once did 
business, a sign said: ``Sold.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside, jackhammers have chewed up Walnut Street in a  
renovation project meant to draw professional offices and 
restaurants. JC Penney and Sears long ago abandoned the downtown 
strip in favor of discount malls that line Muncie's outskirts. 
Those stores have succeeded at more than emptying downtown: From 
1990 to 1996, retail sales jumped 51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Philanthropists are making a cultural mark. In the past few  
years Muncie has gained a cultural center and a new convention 
center with a children's museum. Alumnus David Letterman set up a 
scholarship to Ball State for ``C'' students. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising fortunes mean surging demand for service workers. At  
First Merchants Bank, the starting salary for tellers rose twice in 
a year. It took six months to fill three technology jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Fauquhar may be partly responsible. The founder of Ontario  
Systems says he's paying technology workers $28,000 to $60,000. 
Designers and sales managers make as much as $80,000, in a town 
where $100,000 buys a comfortable ranch house. The business, which 
employed 50 workers in 1990, now has 325. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chamber of Commerce is considering ways to lure workers,  
including a possible ``come back home'' campaign for Ball State 
alumni. ``Everybody's having difficulty getting employees,'' Stefan 
Anderson says. 
</P>
<P>
	The labor market isn't the only way in which Muncie mirrors  
national trends. The city has typified America since the 1920s, 
when Robert and Helen Lynd singled it out in their book, 
``Middletown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The town is still considered a microcosm of the country. In  
Muncie, according to Life magazine, ``you may look at the average 
1937 American as he really is.'' Forty years later, the town's 
ordinariness attracted director Steven Spielberg as the setting for 
his 1977 film, ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The town's cost of living is still 99.5 percent of the national  
average, and its voters serve as a political weather vane. With the 
exception of John Kennedy, they've picked every president in the 
past 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The rising economic tide has not lifted all boats. Manufacturing  
workers have seen their fortunes sink. Service jobs have grown 3.8 
percent a year since 1989 while factory jobs fell 0.6 percent 
annually. Manufacturers employed 35.3 percent of local workers in 
1974. Now it's half that. That mirrors a national decline, from 
25.6 percent of jobs in 1974 to 14.9 percent now. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, glassmaker Ball Corp. moved to Colorado, though its  
founders remain. The Balls, dubbed Muncie's Royal Family by the 
Lynds, gave the town its identity -- and its two largest employers, 
the university and Ball Memorial Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was supposed to be what God intended,'' says Bill  
Spurgeon, retired executive editor of The Muncie Star and Muncie 
Evening Press. ``There was supposed to be glass made in Muncie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 and 1998, manufacturers closed plants and cut more than  
1,500 jobs. Charlene Doss Morales once earned $18.60 an hour at 
Borg-Warner's manual transmission plant. But the market for manuals 
declined, and the production line was sold off. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Mrs. Morales drives her Pontiac Grand Prix (an automatic) 60  
miles to Indianapolis and a part-time job at American Trans Air 
where she makes $7.50 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure I'll ever get up to what Borg-Warner was paying,  
but it'll be rewarding,'' says Ms. Morales, 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of factory workers face a similar plight. The  
production workers who earned $18.60 now average $11.26 an hour, 
according to job relocation program funded by the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, manufacturing cuts have had a limited effect on  
the local economy. Unemployment hasn't exceeded 5 percent, and the 
number of jobs in Delaware County rose 2.7 percent in the past 
year, to 59,800. The city's population, meanwhile, fell from 70,800 
in 1992 to 66,800 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the industrial layoffs, which have been nothing other  
than a hiccup, Muncie and other Indiana cities are putting the 
labor force to work,'' says Patrick M. Barkey, director of Ball 
State's Bureau of Business Research. 
</P>
<P>
	A program trained jobless factory workers for new jobs in  
construction but couldn't fill all the slots. Unemployed and 
unhappily employed workers later enrolled. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Neely saw it as the route to a new career. Laid off a  
decade ago, he took the first job he could find: driving a truck 
for Unitog uniform rentals, picking up dirty garments and dropping 
off clean ones for $14 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	With jobs easier to find this year, Neely, 40, quit to retrain  
as an electrician. He gets $7.50 an hour as an apprentice, but in 
five years he'll earn union scale, now $23.80. He envisions his own 
company one day. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a change he wouldn't have made in the 1980s.  
</P>
<P>
	``Back then unemployment was so high you couldn't even get a job  
at McDonald's,'' says Neely at a construction training site on 
Muncie's southwest side. ``I just told my wife, `There's nothing 
like coming home and feeling good about what you do.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The new economy has also caused something of an identity crisis.  
</P>
<P>
	On both sides of the railroad tracks that neatly divide Muncie's  
professional north side from its blue-collar south side, the roads 
are lined with the GMs, Fords and Chryslers of Munsonians who 
proudly ``buy American.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That slogan has no longer carries the meaning it once did.  
Chryslers are now made by a German-American hybrid, DaimlerChrysler 
AG. The manual transmissions that Borg-Warner once made for GM in 
Muncie are now made in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda, Toyota and Jaguar have leather interiors installed at the  
Muncie shop of Bartlett Corp. And one of the town's newest 
employers will be Honda supplier Keihin Corp. though most Hondas 
here still bear out-of-state plates. Starting in April, the new 
factory will ship air conditioners to the Japanese automaker's 
plants in Ohio. Honda also hires Bartlett Corp. of Muncie to 
install leather interiors. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't have the freedom here in Indiana to bash outsiders  
anymore,'' Ball State's Barkey says, ``because those outsiders are 
providing a lot of the jobs here.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
