<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Honored For War Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAYEUX, France (AP) -- Journalists from Germany, France, Ireland  
and the United States who covered war and its aftermath were 
honored Saturday with the annual Bayeux Prize for War 
Correspondents. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabriel Gruner of the German magazine Stern took the prize for  
written news reporting for his September 1998 coverage in Sudan. 
Gruner was killed while reporting on the conflict in Kosovo this 
year. He was 35. 
</P>
<P>
	American James Nachtwey of the Magnum agency won the photography  
prize for his November 1998 coverage in Indonesia for Time 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Fergal Keane of the BBC took the prize in the television  
category for coverage of conflict in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
<P>
	French reporter Isabelle Dor took the prize in the radio  
category for her coverage of the conflict in Kosovo for France 
Info. 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press photographer Brennan Linsley won the Audience  
Prize for his images of famine in Sudan in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The winners, chosen by an international jury of about 50  
journalists, each received $8,065. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bayeux prizes were first awarded in 1994 to recognize  
journalists who excel in perilous conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayeux was one of the first towns liberated from Nazi occupation  
in the D-Day invasion of Normandy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
