<HEADLINE> Report: Columbus NHL Dispute Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The Columbus Blue Jackets will begin play  
in the National Hockey League next year without Lamar Hunt as an 
owner. 
</P>
<P>
	A tentative agreement was reached that ended Hunt's attempt for  
a share of the team and handed the franchise to the ownership group 
headed by steel magnate John McConnell and his partner, Wolfe 
Enterprises Inc., The Columbus Dispatch reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits each side filed to win control of the team will be  
dropped and Hunt, owner of the NFL's Kansas City Chiefs and the 
Columbus Crew of Major League Soccer, will not receive damages for 
being excluded from McConnell's ownership group, attorneys for both 
sides told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, both sides are going to go on their way,'' said  
Anthony Celebrezze Jr., Hunt's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	John Zeiger, an attorney for McConnell's group, confirmed that  
an agreement was reached, but said the document had not been 
completed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe it would be premature to comment before each of the  
parties have executed the agreement,'' Zeiger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages seeking comment Saturday were left at the offices of  
both attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt, McConnell and Wolfe Enterprises were part of the original  
group of investors who formed Columbus Hockey Ltd. in 1996 to 
pursue an NHL expansion franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	A rift developed in the group after voters rejected a sales-tax  
issue in May 1997 that would have financed a downtown arena and a 
soccer stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell and his partners reached a deal with Nationwide to  
build an arena for the franchise after Hunt turned down a contract 
with Nationwide. They sued Hunt to validate the group's ownership 
claim without him. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 31, the 10th District Court of Appeals upheld a Common  
Pleas Court ruling that said the McConnell group did nothing wrong 
when it acquired the franchise without Hunt. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court, however, reversed the lower court when it  
ruled Hunt did not have to pay McConnell's group $920,000 in legal 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt, of Dallas, accused the NHL and Nationwide of bad-faith  
bargaining and breach of contract. He countersued in a New York 
court, seeking to have the franchise taken away from Columbus and 
asking for $50 million in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Both suits will be dropped in the agreement.  
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, both sides will walk away with where they  
were at the appeals court,'' Celebrezze said. ``Neither side is 
going to file an appeal to the Ohio Supreme Court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jackets will begin play next October in Nationwide  
Arena, which is being built downtown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
