<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lugar Not Sold on Crop Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The owner of the Lugar farm in Indiana is a  
tough sell when it comes to crop insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, the 600-acre corn and soybean operation has not had a  
significant crop loss in more than four decades, and he only 
started buying the federally subsidized insurance a couple of years 
ago because he wanted to see how it worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's possible in America for 41 years to make a profit with or  
without crop insurance,'' says that farmer, Republican Sen. Richard 
Lugar. 
</P>
<P>
	Now as chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee, Lugar has  
delayed work on an overhaul of the insurance system that sharply 
would cut the premiums producers pay for the coverage. The policies 
cover losses from storms or drought; some also protect producers 
from sharp drops in commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The House last month approved legislation that would double the  
federal subsidy for the program to $3 billion a year. The idea is 
to get farmers to buy more coverage, or in many cases to purchase 
the insurance for the first time; a third of the eligible acreage 
nationwide is not insured. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lugar does not think that is the best use of taxpayers'  
money. He has declined to schedule any action on several insurance 
bills that have been introduced in the Senate, including one 
cosponsored by 10 of his committee's 18 members. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's broad consensus on what needs to be done ... and one  
man stands in the way of it,'' said Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	``He sees the entire country from that can't-miss stretch of the  
Corn Belt that he represents'' and ``has very little understanding, 
or, for that matter, concern for farmers producing in areas where 
risk factors are higher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lugar says cutting premiums will encourage farmers to increase  
production of commodities already in surplus and to plant crops in 
areas where they will not grow well. 
</P>
<P>
	He also says a third of the money the government puts into the  
system goes not to farmers but to the companies selling and 
servicing the policies. 
</P>
<P>
	He has introduced legislation that would give the extra cash  
directly to farmers to spend as they choose rather putting it into 
insurance system. To get the money, about $1.3 billion a year, 
farmers would have to show they are taking some steps to reduce 
their financial risk -- buying crop insurance, paying down debt, 
putting money into savings or selling crops under contract, for 
example. 
</P>
<P>
	He has the support of one of the nation's leading agricultural  
economists, Bruce Gardner of the University of Maryland, who says 
the proposed premium cuts would give farmers an extra incentive of 
$8 to $10 an acre to plant crops in areas they otherwise would 
leave alone. 
</P>
<P>
	That is enough of an incentive ``that we can expect to see  
expanded production in risky areas'' and ``weaken commodity prices 
to some extent,'' Gardner, president-elect of the American 
Agricultural Economics Association, told Lugar's committee 
recently. 
</P>
<P>
	But farm groups including the American Farm Bureau Federation  
disagree with Lugar. They support the House legislation and a 
similar Senate bill sponsored by Sens. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., and Bob 
Kerrey, D-Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	Those proposals are seen as a way to help farmers survive  
financially when weather is bad or prices are depressed, as has 
been the case the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Many farmers have declined to buy the coverage because they say  
it is not worth the cost, especially in the East, South and areas 
of the Midwest like Indiana where there usually is enough rain 
every year. Producers in other parts of the country where the 
policies are popular complain they lose their insurance if they 
have a series of weather-related losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Hill, an Iowa corn producer and Farm Bureau member, said  
it is ``is imperative that Congress enact major reforms'' of the 
insurance system. 
</P>
<P>
	The government now pays 13 percent to 57 percent of the premium;  
farmers pick up the rest. Under the House-passed legislation, the 
government would pay from 31 percent to 67 percent, depending on 
the level of coverage. The Roberts-Kerrey bill also would increase 
the subsidy but at different rates. Other Senate bills are targeted 
at helping producers in the South and states growing fruits and 
vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrey pressed Lugar without success last week to schedule votes  
on the insurance issue, saying there is a ``lot of pent-up 
frustration'' among farmers at the Senate's inaction. Lugar said he 
wants to work out a consensus on the issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
