<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olerud Gives Mets One More Miracle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Olerud provided the New York Mets one more  
miracle in this dramatic season. 
</P>
<P>
	Olerud drove in all of New York's runs, including a two-run  
single in the eighth inning off John Rocker, as the Mets staved off 
elimination in the NL Championship Series with a 3-2 victory 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	New York, which trails the NLCS 3-1, still needs an even bigger  
miracle. No team has ever come back from a 3-0 deficit in baseball 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	But for a Mets' team that has been counted out many times this  
season, that won't be their worry until Game 5 on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	After coming from two games back with three to go to force a  
wild-card playoff, winning that tiebreaker in Cincinnati and 
eliminating Arizona in the division series on Todd Pratt's 
10th-inning homer one week ago, no task seems overwhelming. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially after they finally silenced and solved Rocker -- New  
York's Public Enemy No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker saved two of the first three games and hadn't allowed an  
earned run to the Mets all season. He had infuriated New Yorkers by 
saying he hates the Mets, calling their fan ``stupid'' and a 
``tired act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had especially been tough on Olerud and Robin Ventura -- New  
York's best left-handed hitters, who were 0-for-14 against the 
Braves' closer. Manager Bobby Valentine even juggled his lineup to 
keep Olerud and Ventura farther apart in response to Rocker. 
</P>
<P>
	That decision paid off in a different way when Olerud came to  
bat against Rocker with runners on first and second and two outs in 
the eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	Olerud was 2-for-13 in the series before giving the Mets a 1-0  
lead in the sixth inning with a solo homer. Getting a hit off 
Rocker was another matter. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 0-for-9 in his career against Rocker and looked helpless  
in two strikeouts against him in Atlanta. Olerud, a free agent who 
could have been playing his last game as a Met, made sure his New 
York career would last at least one more day. 
</P>
<P>
	After Roger Cedeno and Melvin Mora pulled off a double steal on  
a 1-1 count, Olerud hit a grounder up the middle that bounced off 
shortstop Ozzie Guillen's glove and rolled into shallow center. 
</P>
<P>
	Cedeno and Mora scored easily, with Mora jumping for joy as he  
crossed the plate with the winning run for the second time in two 
weeks. He scored the winning run on a wild pitch in the ninth 
inning to give the Mets a 2-1 win over Pittsburgh on the final day 
of the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Like that run, this one also extended New York's season at least  
another day. They'll need more miracles to keep it going after 
that. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 10:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Loaded With Home Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While battling over the budget on other  
fronts, Republicans and President Clinton agreed on a $99 billion 
measure for veterans, housing and space programs that also is 
loaded with hundreds of projects for lawmakers' home districts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate voted 93-5 to send the bill to Clinton on Friday, a  
day after the House approved it. But with other spending fights 
raging, another stopgap bill will be needed next week to keep 
federal agencies open, and White House officials indicated that 
Clinton would sign one. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders insist they are guided by a desire to  
constrain federal spending, but the veterans-housing measure 
suggests that other forces are afoot as well. It distributes 
hundreds of millions of dollars for home-district projects across 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes nearly six pages of fine print in the Congressional  
Record to list the measure's community development projects, just 
one of several categories of spending directed to specific sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Included is $1.5 million for a loan fund to help Oklahoma City  
recover from the 1995 bombing of its federal building; $250,000 for 
Virginia Beach to expand its marine science museum; $300,000 to 
restore a historic boiler house in Cresson, Pa.; and $400,000 to 
build a memorial in Springfield, Mass., for native son Theodor 
Geisel, better known as Dr. Seuss, who died in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill once faced a veto threat, but that vanished after  
Republicans agreed to add $7 billion above what the House 
originally approved. In the end, NASA, the Environmental Protection 
Agency and veterans' health-care got even more than Clinton 
initially requested, and the GOP dropped plans to cut some 
low-income housing programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure is the 10th of the 13 annual spending bills for  
fiscal 2000, which began Oct. 1. Clinton has vetoed one financing 
the District of Columbia, and is poised to veto a second covering 
foreign aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Three others are still working through Congress in the face of  
veto threats, covering the departments of Labor, Health and Human 
Services, Education, Interior, Commerce, Justice, State, and some 
smaller agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Underlining the remaining tensions, House Appropriations  
Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., accused Democrats of 
withdrawing commitments to support a final $14 billion Interior 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was part of a ``blatant partisan move'' to blame  
Republicans for failing to quickly finish spending work. Democrats 
said they had not made such commitments for a bill they said has 
anti-environmental provisions and lacks enough money. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders want to send Clinton all the bills by next  
Thursday, when a measure keeping agencies temporarily open expires. 
They believe this would bolster their argument that if another 
stopgap extension is needed, it is only because Clinton vetoed 
bills he felt did not spend enough. 
</P>
<P>
	It is all but certain that some of the spending measures won't  
be finished by Thursday night. GOP leaders contemplate a second 
extension that would last a week or more. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no intent to shut the government down, not on our  
part, not on the president's part,'' said House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart signaled that Clinton would  
sign another extension if lawmakers ``come back here and if they 
can make a credible case about why they need an extra week to 
finish the work.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
