<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Lawmaker Touts Charters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While a federal role cannot be denied,  
education in America must return to its local foundations to 
protect the nation's future, a Republican congressional expert on 
education said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Local supervision of schools has been the hallmark and promise  
of American education,'' Rep. Bill Goodling said in the weekly GOP 
radio address. 
</P>
<P>
	``The federal government must aid in those efforts by providing  
special assistance for the disadvantaged, ensuring equal access to 
a quality education'' and gathering information about conditions 
that cross state borders,'' said Goodling, chairman of the House 
Committee on Education and the Workforce. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodling, R-Pa., said the Republican-controlled Congress is  
working on an overhaul of the main government school program, the 
$13.9 billion Elementary and Secondary Education Act. Its current 
target is to amend the act's Title I, which aims to provide quality 
education for poor children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since Title I's inception in 1965,'' Goodling said, ``the  
federal government has poured $120 billion into the program. Yet 
the achievement gap between disadvantaged children and other 
students in our schools continues unabated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He urged Congress to pass a bill coming up for a House vote this  
week that would make it easier for poor children to leave 
inadequate schools in their neighborhoods so they can attend better 
schools elsewhere. The bill cleared Goodling's committee last week 
by a 42-6 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every American child deserves a quality education,'' Goodling  
said. ``We're not talking about Democrat, Republican or Independent 
children. We're talking about all of our children, who are the 
future of this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide money to allow parents of poor children  
to either a better public school or charter school. Money would be 
available to transport them. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodling said the law would help more children attend such  
schools as the Edison-Friendship Charter School in Washington, ``a 
remarkable school in the shadow of the Capitol's dome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charters are public schools, often organized by parents and  
community business leaders, that receive special leeway from most 
regulations as long as their pupils perform at a higher educational 
level. 
</P>
<P>
	Edison-Friendship is a year-old 924-student school with a  
waiting list of 500. It offers character education, an eight-hour 
school day, shorter summer vacations and a home computer for each 
child once their parents receive computer training. 
</P>
<P>
	By its first anniversary in September, students' test scores had  
doubled, Goodling said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also praised a second plan to give states and all public  
schools more flexibility in spending federal money in exchange for 
proven student achievement. Goodling's committee also was passed 
that plan on a party-line vote, and it too is moving to the House. 
Opposed by Democrats for its lack of control over federal money, it 
faces the threat of a veto by President Clinton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
