<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 03:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors in Timor Respond To Nobel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIQUICA, East Timor (AP) -- In the latest trouble spot where  
Doctors Without Borders teams are at work, its medical personnel on 
the ground were too busy to spend much time celebrating their 
group's winning of the 1999 Nobel Peace Prize. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sweltering, makeshift clinic in the town of Liquica, 25  
miles west of the East Timor capital of Dili, a young French doctor 
wiped sweat from his brow between tending today to a steady stream 
of patients: a baby with malaria, a teen-age boy badly bruised from 
what he said was a beating by militiamen, a toddler with a 
suspected case of tuberculosis. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many people here need help,'' said Jean-Olivier Guintran, a  
31-year-old physician from Marseilles who arrived three weeks ago 
as part of a 30-member team from the group. ``The prize, it's very 
nice, but it's the patients that matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Medecins Sans Frontieres, as the group is called in French, is  
one of more than a dozen private relief agencies to rush to East 
Timor, the scene of a humanitarian crisis in the aftermath of an 
Aug. 30 referendum in which East Timorese voted overwhelmingly in 
favor of independence from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote triggered a violent rampage by anti-independence  
militia groups, causing tens of thousands of East Timorese to seek 
shelter in the rugged forest. An estimated 250,000 either fled or 
were driven out of the territory, with most ending up at refugee 
camps in neighboring West Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	An Australian-led peacekeeping force now numbering nearly 8,000  
troops entered the territory Sept. 20 to restore order, but it has 
not yet spread out through the entire province. 
</P>
<P>
	Militias continue to mount a stubborn resistance; a firefight  
today with a reconnaissance team from the international force left 
three of the paramilitary fighters dead, the peacekeepers said. 
</P>
<P>
	As the foreign forces assert control, refugees are trickling  
down from the mountains, where some hid out from the militias for 
weeks. They are suffering from a range of ailments, some readily 
treatable, others much more serious, medical workers say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are seeing lots of problems related to bad sanitation and  
living out in the open -- skin rashes, respiratory infections, 
diarrhea -- but also diseases like malaria and tuberculosis,'' said 
Heidi Quinn, a 34-year-old Doctors Without Borders field 
coordinator from London who was working at the clinic in Liquica. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dili, the France-based group runs a tent clinic in a downtown  
soccer stadium where thousands of people sought shelter during the 
worst of the violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the immediate problems, Doctors Without Borders  
and other relief groups are worried about the coming rainy season, 
the threat of epidemics and a burgeoning demand for medical care as 
more and more of refugees are repatriated. 
</P>
<P>
	Guintran, who joined Doctors only six weeks ago, said he and  
young colleagues saw the Nobel as honoring colleagues of decades 
past who pioneered the group's practice of swooping into difficult 
and dangerous situations to provide care. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all our former teams who deserve this,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Outside the clinic, 32-year-old Jacinta dos Santos cradled her  
feverish 18-month-old daughter as she waited her turn. She had 
arrived at the clinic by foot, a two-hour journey from her village. 
</P>
<P>
	``We heard that there were doctors here,'' she said. ``If not  
for them, we would have only God to help us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 18:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SBC To Upgrade Internet Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- SBC Communications, the local phone company for  
the Southwest and Midwest, plans to spend billions of dollars more 
to bring robust Internet access to its customers sooner, according 
to an industry report. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which just completed its $73 billion acquisition of  
rival baby Bell Ameritech, is expected to announce on Monday that 
it will invest up to $2.5 billion more in upgrading its local phone 
networks over the next three years, the investment firm Goldman 
Sachs &AMP; Co. said in a report to its customers. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC had previously planned to spend about $1 billion per year on  
deploying more robust equipment for Internet services, according to 
past news releases. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Antonio-based company declined to comment on the subject  
of a ``major'' press conference scheduled for Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The main motivation behind SBC's accelerated spending, of  
course, is competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Although dialing up by phone is still the primary means by which  
most people access the Internet at home, cable television and 
wireless communications companies have been moving quickly to 
introduce faster, higher capacity Web service along with calling 
and TV service. AT&AMP;T, for example, has committed more than $100 
billion to buying cable TV systems and upgrading them for those 
purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, phone companies have been rushing to deploy a  
technology called DSL, or digital subscriber line, that enables 
regular copper-phone lines to carry much more data at far greater 
speeds. That increased capacity is becoming vital with the 
increasingly elaborate graphics and capabilities of many Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	But because a DSL signal can't travel more than a few miles  
without fading, telephone companies like SBC will need to spend 
billions to dig up old copper cables and install fiber optic lines 
in every neighborhood they hope to introduce the service. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast with dial-up service, DSL is a live, continuous link  
to the Internet, enabling users to starting surfing with a single 
mouse click. It usually features speeds at least five times faster 
than a dial-up connection through a 56k modem. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC plans to provide DSL speeds 20-to-30 times faster to all its  
customers over the next three years, Goldman Sachs analyst Frank J. 
Governali wrote in the report. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC provides local phone service in most of the Southwest,  
Midwest and California with 59 million access lines. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 03:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers Kill 3 in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- In the bloodiest clash since  
international forces arrived in East Timor nearly a month ago, 
anti-independence militiamen ambushed a peacekeeping patrol today, 
setting off a firefight that left three of the militants dead and 
three wounded, an official said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one in the international force was injured in the clash,  
which took place near the village of Marko, said peacekeeping 
spokesman Col. Mark Kelly. 
</P>
<P>
	Marko is about 10 miles from the border of Indonesian-controlled  
West Timor, where many of the anti-independence militiamen have 
been gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian-led foreign force was deployed to East Timor on  
Sept. 20 to stop a rampage by Indonesian forces and their militant 
allies after the territory voted for independence. Militia leaders 
who fled to West Timor when the peacekeepers arrived have 
repeatedly threatened to launch a guerrilla war against the foreign 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three pro-Indonesian militants have been killed in  
other skirmishes with the peacekeepers over the last 10 days, but 
they weren't as deadly as today's. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly said a reconnaissance patrol of about half a dozen foreign  
soldiers was attacked by a group of about 20 militiamen. After a 
60- to 90-minute battle, a rapid-reaction unit flew to the area by 
helicopter and evacuated the foreign patrol, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The militia units, which were set up earlier this year by the  
Indonesian army, were armed with assault rifles and other automatic 
weapons, Kelly said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the tactics they're employing ... show a level of  
training, a level of aggression,'' he said in Dili, East Timor's 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, Indonesia's military spokesman, Maj. Gen. Sudrajat,  
didn't dispute Kelly's account, saying he is still awaiting a 
report on the battle from his men. However, he denied that any 
paramilitary units have been set up or armed by Indonesia's army. 
</P>
<P>
	``That accusation isn't true at all. The Indonesian military is  
in no position to set up a militia,'' Sudrajat said. ``The 
peacekeepers are only accusing us to find a scapegoat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Indonesian soldiers who controlled East Timor for 24  
years have returned to their country since the territory's vote for 
independence on Aug. 30 and the mayhem that followed. 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeeping forces, which number about 8,000 soldiers, have  
taken control of heavily damaged Dili, and are now being deployed 
to most other cities in the territory. They also are boosting their 
presence along the border with West Timor, where a clash last week 
with militants and Indonesian forces led Jakarta to accuse the 
peacekeepers of violating Indonesia's sovereignty. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there are still many remote areas of East Timor which  
the foreign forces do not yet control. 
</P>
<P>
	In another development, the United Nations said it will send a  
five-member team to East Timor to investigate allegations of 
atrocities there following the independence vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, an emergency session of the U.N. Human Rights  
Commission voted 32-12 for the international inquiry, calling for 
an ``adequate representation of Asian experts.'' The team announced 
Friday will be led by Sonia Picado of Costa Rica and will include 
members from India and Papua New Guinea. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia has rejected an international inquiry, saying its own  
national rights commission should investigate abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Wiranto, Indonesia's military commander, told the Straits  
Times newspaper in Singapore on Friday that there is no evidence 
that mass killings occurred in the territory. He said U.N. 
officials and relief agencies, which initially reported that 
thousands of East Timorese were killed by Indonesian forces, 
exaggerated the death tolls to discredit his soldiers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
