<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catalan Leader Challenged in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- Jordi Pujol, the Catalan regional  
president and national power broker, wears a smile on his campaign 
posters, but he faces a tough challenge to his 19 years office in 
Sunday's regional election. 
</P>
<P>
	For many Spaniards, Pujol, 69, personifies Catalan nationalism --  
a local hero ever since his defiance of former dictator Francisco 
Franco's ban on using the ``subversive'' Catalan language earned 
him two years in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	But cracks have appeared in his aura of indestructibility. For  
the first time since taking office in 1980, Pujol faces a serious 
rival, popular Socialist Pasqual Maragall, a former Barcelona 
mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time, there is a candidate with a powerful  
political personality of his own who is not afraid of Pujol,'' says 
Catalan political analyst Rafael Jorba. 
</P>
<P>
	As Barcelona mayor from 1982 to 1997, Maragall, 58, championed  
urban renewal and brought international prestige to the city by 
staging the 1992 Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	A center-left politician with a modern, media-friendly image,  
Maragall's campaign is based on the assumption that Catalonia's 6 
million people are ready to move beyond the Pujol era. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need a hurricane to sweep everything clear,'' Maragall told  
supporters in Barcelona. 
</P>
<P>
	But outside the city, people worry that Maragall will give  
priority to projects in Barcelona and the surrounding industrial 
zone, populated by migrants running from unemployment elsewhere in 
Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maragall was a good mayor of Barcelona, but Pujol is a real  
Catalan, he's one of ours,'' Agustin Fontanez, 50, said after Pujol 
slapped him on the back as he campaigned through a local market in 
the rural town of Tortosa. 
</P>
<P>
	For Pujol, being a ``real Catalan'' has little to do with  
ancestry or secessionist dreams. He frequently insists Catalan 
identity is open to anybody living in the wealthy northeastern 
region. He does not seek secession from Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the last 19 years, Pujol's very personalized style has  
succeeded in identifying Catalonia with him alone,'' says Jorba, 
pointing to Pujol's tireless promotion of the Catalan language. 
</P>
<P>
	Pujol also seeks credit for constantly fighting for Catalonia's  
interests in Madrid. Over the years, his conservative Convergence 
and Union party has thrown its weight behind minority national 
governments in return for privileges for Catalonia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
