<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Deny Hiring Permission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles can forget about trying to  
hire New York Yankees executive Gordon Blakeley as their next 
general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees owner George Steinbrenner has denied permission for the  
Orioles to interview Blakeley, team sources told The Associated 
Press on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Blakeley is the director of international and professional  
scouting for the Yankees, and his speciality is Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Blakeley was instrumental in bringing pitcher Orlando ``El  
Duque'' Hernandez and top infield prospect Alfonso Soriano to the 
World Series champions. He also helped in the pursuit of pitcher 
Hideki Irabu. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles fired GM Frank Wren on Oct. 7, after his first  
season with the team. Earlier this week, Wren was hired by Atlanta 
as an assistant general manager. Baltimore also dismissed manager 
Ray Miller the same day after a disappointing 78-84 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Blakeley is based at the Yankees' complex in Tampa, Fla., and is  
part of team's inner circle in decisions involving talent. He is in 
the middle of a multiyear contract. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Steinbrenner has occasionally blocked other teams  
from talking to his executives when jobs became available. Sources 
said the Orioles sought permission to speak with Blakeley this week 
and were turned down. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinbrenner was in Boston on Saturday, watching the Yankees  
lose to Boston 13-1 in Game 3 of the AL championship series. 
Despite the most lopsided loss in their postseason history, the 
Yankees lead 2-1 in the best-of-7 matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Yankees promoted Mark Newman to director of  
baseball operations. That move, which elevated to a position 
ranking ahead of general manager Brian Cashman, came amid 
speculation that other teams wanted to interview him for general 
manager vacancies. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinbrenner, sources said, let it be known that he did not  
intend for Newman or Blakeley to go work for another team while 
under contract to the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles, who have interviewed third base coach Sam Perlozzo  
for the managing job, have not yet talked to any candidates for the 
GM spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore is said to want to set up a front office system much  
like the one used by the Yankees, with several people playing key 
parts in the decision-making process, and thought Blakeley would be 
a good person to head it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
