<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Upends Calif. Town of Ludlow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUDLOW, Calif. (AP) -- David Rockwell stood in the middle of his  
kitchen on Saturday staring at the broken memories on the floor. 
Photographs, china, ceramic birds, all damaged or destroyed when a 
magnitude-7.0 earthquake struck this remote desert town. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell and his girlfriend, Jackie Adams, have one of 22 mobile  
homes in the Ludlow Mobile Home Park. Every one was knocked off its 
foundations, leaving the town's only residential neighborhood at a 
tilt. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's been saving almost all of this since we've been  
together,'' he said, picking up broken champagne glasses, given to 
them to toast their new life in Ludlow six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The epicenter was just a few miles south of Ludlow in a desolate  
mining patch called Hector. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten miles west of town, an Amtrak train on its way from Chicago  
to Los Angeles derailed when the quake knocked 21 of 25 cars off 
its rails, slightly injuring four people. Five miles away, an 
overpass on Interstate 40 was cracked at both ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``This kind of thing can put you out of business. It was a  
miracle it wasn't any harder. With the train and the overpass and 
the problems here, it's pretty bad,'' said town owner John Knoll. 
</P>
<P>
	Ludlow, founded in 1882 by the Ludlow Mining Co., was once a  
booming frontier post along the Santa Fe Trail. Route 66 was built 
through the town in the 1920s, making Ludlow a key stop on the 
2,448-mile ``mother road'' between Chicago and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Knoll and his brother bought Ludlow in 1978, a few years before  
Route 66 was decommissioned. Valued at $7 million, the town 125 
miles east of Los Angeles includes the boarded up Ludlow Fire 
Department, Ludlow Cafe and Ludlow Arco. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knolls provide free housing for 43 employees and  
transportation for a dozen more who are bused in from Barstow every 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	At the mobile home park, air conditioning and heating units were  
crumpled on driveways, staircases overturned, satellite dishes 
collapsed and windows shattered. 
</P>
<P>
	The three houses in Ludlow were still upright, but there was  
extensive damage, including crushed china, smashed pictures and 
dangling light fixtures. 
</P>
<P>
	Knoll said he even lost his toilet. ``It just rolled over on its  
side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes after the 2:46 a.m. quake, nearly all of the  
town's residents gathered in a parking lot to make sure everyone 
was OK, check damage and ride out a wave of aftershocks. 
</P>
<P>
	They were joined by about half a dozen motorists who drove in to  
find the gas pumps out of commission because of a power outage. The 
next station is 35 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Ford was on his way home from Colorado to Lake Elsinore.  
</P>
<P>
	``We stopped here to get gas on our way to Colorado,'' he said.  
``We figured we could get it here on the way back. Now, I don't 
have enough to get to the next station.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Motorist John Ryan was so desperate he paid $20 for a 5-gallon  
can of gas from another driver hauling jet skis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not staying here any longer than I have to,'' he said  
following an aftershock. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 13:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Parts of the Southeast soaked in rain from Hurricane Irene on  
Saturday, while storms also struck the Midwest. Much of the West 
was dry. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain associated with Irene fail from Florida to the Carolinas.  
</P>
<P>
	A relatively weak storm system affected the Great Lakes and  
parts of lower Ohio Valley, with clouds and some showers. The 
clouds covered most of Wisconsin and Michigan through Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	The cold front trailing into the middle states and moisture  
moving up from the north also brought increasing clouds over east 
Kansas through east Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind this front is much colder air. Snow fell in the central  
Colorado Rockies. Snow also fell in Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	A few light snow showers were scattered about Nebraska and  
northwest Kansas, mixed with rain. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the rest of the nation, the Northeast was generally dry  
and most of the West was partly cloudy to fair. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 8 in  
Stanley, Idaho, to an early-afternoon high of 90 in McAllen, Texas. 
With the wind chill, it felt like minus 9 in Rawlins, Wyo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
