<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Stops Gambling -- for a Minute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The 7.0-magnitude earthquake in the Southern  
California desert did what a lack of sleep and a lot of bad luck 
can rarely do: stop gambling in Las Vegas for a few moments. 
</P>
<P>
	But only for a few.  
</P>
<P>
	Not long after frightened guests left high-rise rooms for  
ground-level casinos early Saturday, the cherries and oranges soon 
started spinning again in the slots and gamblers restacked chips on 
black and red. Wagers picked up at a faster pace than before. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figure if I'm up, I may as well lose some more change,''  
said Martha Anderson of Chicago, cradling her cup of coins for the 
slots at Caesars Palace. ``I don't think I could go back to sleep 
now, anyway. It scared the devil out of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Candy McCain of Phoenix only briefly stopped feeding coins into  
slots at The Mirage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't sure exactly what was going on, but then I saw the  
signs swaying and the leaves on the fake palms rustling, so I 
thought it must be an earthquake,'' she said. ``When it stopped, I 
started playing again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The quake struck at 2:46 a.m. and was centered 150 miles to the  
west, causing the hotels along the famed Strip to sway, but there 
were no reports of damage or injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	But it rattled the nerves of many out-of-towners.  
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Taylor of Boerne, Texas, and friends Dorothy and Sherry  
Garner of Wister, Okla., were hesitant to go back inside their 
hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first I thought it was hail,'' Taylor said, still looking  
jittery as she sat on a bench outside the Mirage. ``I jumped out of 
bed and realized the room was swaying back and forth. We were on 
the 19th floor and it really seemed to move a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dorothy Garner, 66, said she couldn't believe she made it down  
18 flights of stairs so quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It must have been some kind of record,'' she said. ``I don't  
even like to use stairs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The quake also was a first for Veronica DeMarzo of New York.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm 71 years old and I've never felt anything like that,'' she  
said. ``It shook me right out of my bed.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
