<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buddy Bell May Be Rockies' Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Colorado Rockies reportedly are close to  
hiring Cincinnati Reds farm director Buddy Bell as their next 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell could be hired as soon as next week, The Denver Post and  
Denver Rocky Mountain News reported in Saturday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell reportedly will fly to Denver next week for a formal  
interview with Rockies general manager Dan O'Dowd, vice president 
Keli McGregor and owners Jerry McMorris, Charlie Monfort and Dick 
Monfort. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd did not return telephone messages left by The Associated  
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd said he and Bell have had preliminary discussions, but  
the deal has not been finalized. O'Dowd denied reports that Bell 
has already been hired. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's premature,'' O'Dowd told the Post. ``It could turn out  
that way, but we don't have the day firmed up yet on when we can 
get Buddy out here. I will say that I'm ready to take this to the 
next stage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd said there is no deadline for hiring a manager, but it is  
likely to happen in the next week. Major League Baseball has a 
hiring blackout in effect during the World Series, which begins 
Oct. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell said he is not interested in the Cleveland Indians  
managerial job that opened up with Friday's dismissal of Mike 
Hargrove. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of my focus is on getting this done with the Rockies,''  
Bell told the News. ``I'm excited about getting a chance to talk to 
Jerry McMorris and the Monforts, and seeing if this is a fit for 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	None of the other managerial candidates interviewed so far --  
Rich Donnelly, Clint Hurdle, Lynn Jones, Ken Griffey Sr., Carlos 
Tosca and Willie Randolph -- have met with the Rockies' owners. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd also had an initial telephone conversation on Thursday  
with Hall of Famer George Brett, a vice president of the Kansas 
City Royals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did talk to Dan, and it was a very nice talk,'' Brett told  
the Post. ``But anything more than that better come from them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd interviewed Tosca, the Arizona Diamondbacks bench coach,  
on Thursday, and said he was impressed. The Cuban-born Tosca, 46, 
has managed 16 years at every level of the minor leagues, finishing 
first five times. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd described Tosca as a viable candidate with few  
weaknesses. But he reportedly has been telling other candidates 
that Bell is his first choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell began his 18-year big league playing career with Cleveland  
from 1972-78, and was Hargrove's bench coach from 1994-95. 
</P>
<P>
	One hitch in signing Bell could be his reluctance to move his  
family from Cincinnati, but Bell reportedly has not raised the 
issue in discussions with the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	``That may be, but if that's the case, he's not going to be the  
manager of this club,'' O'Dowd said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't discussed any specific issues with the Rockies at  
all,'' Bell told the Post. ``I have talked to Danny a couple times, 
but not about that. I'd like to get to the point where we will 
consider each other.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
