<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders Differ on Campaign Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gathered in a Capitol conference room, Speaker  
Dennis Hastert and other House GOP leaders wanted to learn results 
of a focus group conducted days earlier to gauge reaction to a 
series of campaign commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	According to participants in the session, who spoke on condition  
of anonymity, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the GOP Whip and a proponent 
of a vigorous advertising effort, said he had been informed the 
commercials had been well received when viewed by the audience 
assembled to see them. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, the campaign committee chairman  
who was less eager to commit to a costly ad campaign, said he had 
been told the results were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	A staff aide was called on to resolve the differing opinions,  
but the event provided an awkward moment for the leadership, 
according to several GOP aides who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, on an early autumn evening, the leadership met  
again in Hastert's office to view the commercial itself. The 
decision was to go ahead and air it. 
</P>
<P>
	Even then, there was dissent when Davis convened the executive  
committee of the National Republican Campaign Committee the 
following day. 
</P>
<P>
	One member of the group, Rep. David Hobson, R-Ohio, objected  
according to several sources. Hobson's concern was that the wording 
of their ads would complicate their stated purpose, which was to 
enlist Democrats in the effort to safeguard the Social Security 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobson declined comment.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
