<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gates: Watch Murdoch's Influence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Bill Gates thinks if anyone wants to take over the  
world, it's the man who accused him of wanting to -- media tycoon 
Rupert Murdoch. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the BBC scheduled to air this weekend, the  
Microsoft Corp. chairman says: ``He's hiding behind me. He's your 
man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gates says running Microsoft is ``not like owning a newspaper,''  
referring to Murdoch's News Corp. empire, which includes newspapers 
in the United States, England and Australia, as well as the 20th 
Century Fox movie studio, Fox Television, the Los Angeles Dodgers 
baseball team and satellite TV networks on several continents. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone who owns a newspaper can pick up the phone to the  
editor and say `run headlines I like,''' Gates says. ``What we do 
is create tools like a word processor that lets people express 
their ideas and we're not at all involved in how they choose to use 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing we're involved with has democratized communications,  
and anyone can publish on the Internet. You don't have to own a TV 
channel or a newspaper.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
