<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Giuliani Slipping in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Whether or not they will be able to cast a  
vote for next year's Senate race in New York, Americans are looking 
less favorably upon anticipated candidates Rudolph Giuliani and 
Hillary Rodham Clinton, according to a poll released Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The CBS News poll found that 16 percent of those questioned  
nationwide earlier this month gave Giuliani, New York City's 
Republican mayor, an ``unfavorable'' rating. Six percent found him 
unfavorable in a March 1998 poll. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Giuliani's favorable rating also rose during the same  
period, with 21 percent of respondents reporting a favorable 
impression of the mayor, up from 16 percent in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeasterners are driving the ratings dive for Giuliani, with  
24 percent reporting unfavorable impressions of him this month, up 
from 7 percent in March 1998, the poll found. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani's popularity continues to rise among Republicans, with  
29 percent reporting favorable impressions of the mayor, up from 20 
percent in March 1998. Negative ratings among Republicans grew 
seven percentage points, from 3 percent to 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Mrs. Clinton, 36 percent of those polled this month had  
unfavorable impressions of her, up from 20 percent in January 1999. 
Forty percent said they had a favorable impression of the first 
lady, down from 55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollsters found a drop in the number of women who look favorably  
on Mrs. Clinton and an increase in the number who see her 
unfavorably. Thirty-one percent of respondents this month said they 
have an unfavorable opinion of her, up from 17 percent in January 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-four percent said they have a favorable impression of Mrs.  
Clinton, down from 61 percent in January 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	With the election still more than a year away, neither Giuliani  
nor Mrs. Clinton has formally announced for the seat being vacated 
by Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oct. 3-4 telephone poll of 871 adults has a margin of error  
of 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll earlier this month of New York voters found Giuliani and  
Mrs. Clinton in a statistical dead heat. 
</P>
<P>
	That poll, released Oct. 6 from Marist College's Institute for  
Public Opinion, found the mayor favored by 46 percent of the 
state's voters, while 42 percent backed Mrs. Clinton. Other polls 
have also shown them about even. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
