<HEADLINE> Ramsey Case May Get New Prosecutor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Gov. Bill Owens will meet with Boulder  
District Attorney Alex Hunter Monday night to discuss the 
possibility of appointing a special prosecutor for the JonBenet 
Ramsey case, one of Hunter's advisors said. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury investigation of the Ramsey case, launched by  
Hunter Sept. 15, 1998, ended Wednesday without any indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens announced Wednesday that he would consider appointing a  
special prosecutor to review the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams County District Attorney Bob Grant, who is part of  
Hunter's team of advisors on the Ramsey case, said of the meeting: 
``The only person I'm sure will be there is me, since I haven't 
talked to anyone else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant said he expects Hunter's grand jury team of Michael Kane,  
Bruce Levin, Mitch Morrissey and Denver-area prosecutors Bill 
Ritter, Dave Thomas and Jim Peters to be present at the meeting as 
well. Ritter, Thomas and Peters are from Denver, Jefferson County 
and Arapahoe County, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Amy Sampson, Owen's acting press secretary, declined to reveal  
the time or location of the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that they are planning a meeting soon, but they are  
still working out the details,'' Sampson said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said earlier that JonBenet's parents, John and Patsy  
Ramsey, remain under an ``umbrella of suspicion'' in the December 
1996 slaying of JonBenet, 6, at their Boulder home. Hunter said 
Thursday that they have not been eliminated from the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ramseys have said all along they are innocent.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
