<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Arrests Outlawed Muslims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Egyptian police have arrested 20 senior  
members of the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood and accused them of 
various anti-government activities, security officials said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests took place Thursday in Cairo's southern neighborhood  
of Maadi, where 16 members were meeting at an office of the 
Engineers' Union, said the officials who spoke on customary 
condition of anonymity. Four others were brought from their homes, 
the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Formed in 1928, the Muslim Brotherhood was banned in 1954, but  
was tolerated by the government until 1995, when authorities 
arrested at least 200 brotherhood members. Since then, the 
government has cracked down on the group, accusing its members of 
supporting the Islamic insurgency that broke out in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muslim Brotherhood maintains that it does not support  
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those detained was Mukhtar Nouh, a well-known lawyer who  
defends Muslim fundamentalists. Nouh is the treasurer of the 
Lawyers' Union and is a former member of the Egyptian parliament. 
He is also a member of the brotherhood's consultative council. 
</P>
<P>
	Nouh's wife, Kholoud, said she has not been in touch with her  
husband since he was arrested midday Thursday, adding that security 
agents searched their house on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officials said state security prosecutors have ordered  
that the 20 men be imprisoned 15 days for interrogation. 
</P>
<P>
	The men have been accused of joining an illegal organization  
trying to overthrow the government, holding illegal meetings in 
order to revive the brotherhood, infiltrating unions to make their 
members carry out anti-government activities and having 
anti-government printed material, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests came after the Court of Cassation on Sunday upheld a  
1996 ruling by a Cairo appeals court that called for 
government-appointed custodians to take control of the Lawyers' 
Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The government apparently is attempting to prevent the  
brotherhood from taking control of the union, which counts up to 
20,000 members. 
</P>
<P>
	Maamoun Hodeibi, the brotherhood's spokesman, told The  
Associated Press that the meeting in Maadi had nothing to do with 
the brotherhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is it a crime to be concerned about the people?'' Hodeibi  
asked. ``People talking about their unions -- where is the crime in 
that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among those arrested were Mohammed Abdel-Badie,  
secretary-general of the Veterinarians' Union; Mohammed Ali Bishr, 
secretary-general of the Lawyers' Union; and Saad Zaghloul, 
secretary-general of Cairo's Doctors' Union. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
