<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. A&AMP;T Defeats Morgan State 30-6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE, Md. (AP) --North Carolina A&AMP;T defeated Morgan State,  
30-6, Saturday in a game that had coach Stanley Mitchell 
questioning the abilities of his players. 
</P>
<P>
	Armand Walters in the first quarter raced past Turnell Purkett  
on a deep post to catch Willie McGirt's pass and wade into the end 
zone to give Morgan State a 6-0 lead with 12:25 remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	The play made up more than a third of the offensive yardage the  
team would gain in the 26:47 that it held the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The running attack, found in last week's victory over Towson,  
would get lost again with less than 2 yards per carry. And the 
defense would give up more than 400 yards for the third consecutive 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching his team penalized for almost as many yards (171)  
as his team gained (173), Mitchell was left to consider some harsh 
truths. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have ball players who aren't ball players, that's the truth  
of the matter,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Freshman Marque Brown got Morgan in field-goal position, but a  
bad snap on a 30-yard field goal attempt was followed by a pass by 
K.C. Vasquez. Brown then got a concussion at the end of the half 
and gave way to T.J. Stallings, a kick returner with limited 
quarterback experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell then briefly went to receiver Marc Lester who threw an  
interception in his only attempt, returned 27 yards to the Morgan 
State 4 by A&AMP;T's Daryl Klugh, setting up a 4-yard touchdown run by 
Adrian Parks that made the final score with 14:56 left to play. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
