<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Budroyale Wins Goodwood Handicap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Left out of an early speed duel between  
Old Trieste and Hollycombe, Budroyale made up ground at the top of 
the stretch and went on to a neck victory in Saturday's $500,000 
Goodwood Breeders' Cup Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Garrett Gomez, Budroyale covered 1 1/8 miles in 1:48 1-5  
and paid $20, $4.40 and $2.10 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, coming off a victory in the Pacific Classic  
at Del Mar two months ago, finished second under David Flores and 
returned $2.60 and $2.10. Old Trieste and Chris McCarron was 
another three lengths back in third and paid $2.10 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I had him coming to the three-eighths pole,'' Flores  
said of the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to put pressure on him and get away from him. But I  
could see Budroyale was coming in with me,'' he said. ``In the 
stretch, my horse dug in, and he was just trying so hard. But the 
other one, he didn't stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Budroyale inserted himself into the picture for next month's  
Breeders' Cup Classic at Gulfstream. The 6-year-old is already 
eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	``He beat two of the best horses in the world in Old Trieste and  
General Challenge, and the others were no slouches either,'' 
trainer Ted West Jr. said. ``The fact that he can look those horses 
in the eye and run them down like that, I think we have to consider 
the Breeders' Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, who carried co-high weight of 120 pounds with  
Old Trieste, ran fourth before moving up on the stretch turn. The 
3-year-old trailed by seven lengths when Old Trieste and Hollycombe 
hooked up in the early stages. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't his kind of race,'' trainer Bob Baffert said. ``All  
of a sudden, he was seven lengths back and that's not good. He's 
not a horse that can quicken, he's got to run them into the ground 
early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Mike Puype had just the opposite problem. He didn't like  
seeing Old Trieste lured into a speed duel. 
</P>
<P>
	``He breaks to run and he was instantly hooked and the other  
horse (Hollycombe) was just running off with him,'' Puype said. 
``Chris took him back, but it's not his style to sit back and 
reverse. He's a free-running frontrunner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	West wasn't worried when Budroyale lagged behind.  
</P>
<P>
	``If this horse gets his head in front or somebody doesn't pass  
him at the top of the stretch, he's almost impossible to pass,'' he 
said. ``Garrett said the other horses just get sick of fighting 
because he just doesn't stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert had called General Challenge the most talented horse  
he's ever trained. He said owner John Mabee would have to decide 
whether to run the 3-year-old in the Breeders' Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope he's not discouraged after seeing him get beat  
like that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said the victory, along with River Keen's upset of the  
East Coast's top horses in last week's Jockey Club Gold Cup at 
Belmont, further muddled the year-end picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no standout,'' he said. ``It's wide open.''  
</P>
<P>
	In the $250,000 Oak Tree Breeders' Cup Mile, Silic defeated  
Bouccaneer by one length under Corey Nakatani. Silic covered one 
mile on the turf in 1:33 3-5 and paid $6.40, $4.20 and $3.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Bouccaneer, a French-bred like the winner, returned $8.40 and  
$4.40, while British-bred Brave Act was another length back in 
third and paid $2.60 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Silic and Brave Act are pointing toward the Breeders' Cup  
Mile. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
