<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tiny Town Tries To Dodge Rising Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHURCHS FERRY, N.D. (AP) -- Paul Christenson has no idea yet what  
kind of offer he might get to move from his home. He doesn't care 
either. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old mechanic and life-long resident of Churchs Ferry  
made up his mind long ago -- before Devils Lake began threatening 
the town -- that this is home. 
</P>
<P>
	Money won't change that.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not moving,'' Christenson says, his grease-caked hands and  
forearms wrestling with a broken farm truck transmission in his 
repair shop. ``I've been here my whole life. I built my house from 
nothing, I built my shop, my business from nothing. I'm not willing 
to give that up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is a decision being faced by every one of the 113 residents  
of this tiny farming town in north-central North Dakota. Devils 
Lake, whose shoreline was miles away from the town only a few years 
ago, has methodically crept up to its doorstep and is knocking. 
</P>
<P>
	Water threatens the town's largest business, the local grain  
elevator, as well as the city's sewer system. Officials believe it 
is only a matter of time before the 42 occupied homes and handful 
of other businesses are in danger too. 
</P>
<P>
	A wet cycle in the Upper Plains has caused Devils Lake to rise  
nearly 25 feet since 1992. With no outlet and in flat country such 
as this, it means the water has spread over tens of thousands of 
acres and more than doubled in total size. Year by year, it 
swallows more land. 
</P>
<P>
	This month, state and federal agencies announced a controversial  
plan to dredge a permanent outlet from Devils Lake into the nearby 
Sheyenne River to help stabilize the lake level. But construction 
could take two years or more, which many believe will be too long 
to save Churchs Ferry. 
</P>
<P>
	So the Federal Emergency Management Agency plans to use about $2  
million to buy out the homes in Churchs Ferry and move the 
residents away before the water soaks in. 
</P>
<P>
	But to move is a difficult, almost unconscionable, proposition  
for some. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis Haugeberg is manager of the BTR Farmers Cooperative grain  
elevator and a resident for 10 years. He understands the 
apprehension, but believes the town may have no choice but move. 
</P>
<P>
	``To sit here and see the lake rise and begin to wreak havoc on  
my business, on my customers and friends who I care about is very 
traumatic,'' Haugeberg says. ``But with that said, I see the 
potential of this buyout program bringing this to a closure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is an understatement to say this is a close-knit town.  
Everyone knows everybody else. Many have lived here their entire 
lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The buyout plan has been about the only topic of conversation in  
recent weeks. It is debated constantly in living rooms, at the 
grain elevator and at the only bar in town, The Water Hole, which 
shares a building with the all-volunteer fire department. There are 
just three stop signs and no paved streets. The cost of living here 
is very low and most people own their homes outright. 
</P>
<P>
	Longtime resident Jim Savaloja, his voice quivering and tears  
filling his eyes, tried desperately to describe his anxiety and 
apprehension at a recent town meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The town of Churchs Ferry,'' he said, clutching his shirt  
above his heart, ``is contemplating an act that can cause its own 
demise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of us fully intended to live out our lives here,'' he  
added, ``knowing that neighbors would keep an eye on each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, neighbors await as officials prepare appraisals of each of  
the homes. The government eventually will make buyout offers on 
each piece of property, which homeowners can accept or reject. 
Since the buyout program is voluntary, no one will be forced to 
move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people realize that we're not fighting the government  
here,'' says Kyle Nelson, a bank vice president in nearby Leeds, 
who moved to town three years ago with his wife. ``It's David vs. 
Goliath, but it's important to realize that Goliath isn't the 
government, it's Mother Nature.''	   But what worries many are the consequences if half the town's 
residents or more accept the offers. Will there be enough of a tax 
base to continue providing services to those who remain? And what 
will happen if the waters do invade town? 
</P>
<P>
	Churchs Ferry already has suffered its share of disappointments.  
Founded in 1886, the town once thrived when the farm economy was 
healthy. But the population has dwindled in recent decades. 
Businesses have closed. The school was forced to shut its doors in 
1988 and was turned into a community center. Half the homeowners 
are over the age of 62. Many are on fixed incomes. 
</P>
<P>
	For those who are considering the buyout, the concern is whether  
the ``market price'' government officials have promised will be 
enough to buy a comparable home in a new community. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials say they will pressure no one to move and  
will help those who stay behind. But they are still urging 
homeowners to give serious consideration to the buyout offers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are safe places to go,'' says Maj. Gen. Keith Bjerke,  
the head of the North Dakota National Guard, one of the agencies 
involved in the buyout program. ``There are people, communities, 
begging for people just like you to be their neighbors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christenson likes the neighbors he has. His repair shop is next  
to his boyhood home. He, his wife and two children live in a home 
they built themselves. It's complete with a large deck and 
above-ground swimming pool. 
</P>
<P>
	Christenson believes the threat posed by Devils Lake has been  
exaggerated and hopes residents will turn down the buyout offers 
and stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``The water is a long ways away, as far as I'm concerned,'' he  
says. ``It's not that the buyout is a bad deal, it isn't. I just 
think it's not time yet. I hope people will stick around.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
