<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Arrest Five in Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Police arrested five men under Ireland's  
anti-terrorism laws and seized two rifles Saturday in their 
crackdown on suspected Irish Republican Army dissidents opposed to 
the group's cease-fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were arrested early Saturday at their homes in Dublin,  
said a police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests are the latest in an Irish police clampdown on IRA  
dissidents over recent weeks. Under Ireland's anti-terrorism laws, 
they can be held for up to 72 hours before being charged or 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRA has maintained a cease-fire since July 1997, but  
violence has continued and has been blamed on renegades opposed to 
the Northern Ireland peace process. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, a stash of guns, ammunition and Semtex  
explosives was uncovered in southwest Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	In other news, six men who were arrested Thursday and were being  
questioned about a suspected IRA transatlantic gun-smuggling 
operation were released without charge, police said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Another six people who had been arrested Tuesday and questioned  
about the plot have also been released. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the IRA denied it had authorized any arms-smuggling  
efforts after four people were arrested in Florida and Pennsylvania 
and charged in connection with the discovery of weapons being 
mailed to Ireland. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
