<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Islamic Groups Warn U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan's hard-line Islamic groups  
vowed today to protect suspected terrorist Osama bin Laden and 
warned both the United States and United Nations that sanctions 
against Afghanistan would anger Muslims worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the U. N. Security Council gave Afghanistan's Taliban  
rulers one month to hand over bin Laden for trial in connection 
with the U.S. Embassy bombings in Africa or face limited sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Reacting a day later, the Sipah-e-Sahaba -- a militant Sunni  
Muslim group blamed for the deaths of hundreds of Pakistan's 
minority Shiite Muslims -- said the United Nations was acting at the 
behest of the United States and warned that Muslims worldwide would 
react. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is hatred for the United States among Muslims,'' said  
Zia-ul Qasmi, a spokesman for the radical group. ``The time will 
come when Muslims will strongly react and this will be bad for 
Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We support Osama because he is a great fighter who is  
continuing his jihad (holy war) in Afghanistan,'' Qasmi said. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been no official reaction from Afghanistan's Taliban  
religious army, which rules about 90 percent of their war-battered 
homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview today in Kabul, Afghan Commerce Minister Faizl  
Mohammed Faizan said sanctions will not hurt the Taliban 
government, only Afghanistan's people. He refused to say whether 
sanctions would prompt the Taliban to reconsider their protection 
of bin Laden. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taliban have refused to hand over bin Laden, saying they  
have no extradition treaty with the United States or proof of the 
exiled Saudi's involvement in terrorist activities. They also say 
bin Laden is an honored guest in Afghanistan and will be protected 
by the Taliban because protection of guests is deeply rooted in 
Afghan culture and tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	In its ultimatum Friday, the United Nations said it would freeze  
the Taliban's assets and ban flights owned, leased or operated by 
the Taliban's Ariana airlines or landing internationally unless bin 
Laden is handed over. 
</P>
<P>
	Islamic groups in Pakistan, many of whom are believed to get  
training in Afghanistan, say the U.N. ultimatum reflects 
Washington's control over the global body. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan's right-wing Jamaat-e-Islami group, one of the  
best-organized religious parties in Pakistan, said bin Laden is a 
symbol to mujahedeen, or Islamic freedom fighters battling 
pro-secular regimes throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bin Laden is not just a name, but a phenomena that embodies  
the jihads being fought throughout this region from Central Asia to 
Kashmir,'' said Munawar Hassan, a Jamaat-e-Islami spokesman. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
