<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baylor Mulls Taking Brewers Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Atlanta Braves hitting coach Don Baylor said he  
has spoken with Milwaukee general manager Dean Taylor several times 
in recent weeks about becoming the Brewers' manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've talked about the organization itself, the type of  
players they have, what they're trying to do,'' Baylor said Friday. 
``We never talked about a contract, so we haven't gotten that 
far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor, in an interview with the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel,  
said he had a three-hour talk with Taylor in Atlanta soon after 
Taylor was named general manager Sept. 21 and has spoken with him 
six or seven times since. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor has also talked with Cincinnati coach Ken Griffey Sr.,  
planned to meet today with San Diego coach Davey Lopes and Monday 
with Arizona coach Carlos Tosca. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor, who managed the Colorado Rockies for six years, denied  
reports of an oral agreement to manage the Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no agreement,'' he said. ``We made some progress. We  
have not talked about length of contract or a dollar figure 
whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also denied having no interest in Milwaukee because of what  
he felt was an insincere interview by Brewers general manager Sal 
Bando in 1991. Bando then hired Phil Garner. Both were fired a few 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sal is no longer there so that's not a factor,'' Baylor said.  
``I had a bad experience, but that's not going to be the deciding 
factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Dean and I have gotten along great.''  
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta general manager John Schuerholz, Taylor's former boss,  
said he would not give permission to another team to hire Baylor 
while the Braves are in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the significance of Taylor's telephone calls to him,  
Baylor said: ``I'd say there is a pursuit going on.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
