<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Families Grieve for Texas Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLEASANTON, Texas (AP) -- Grieving relatives and police on  
Saturday remembered two of the three officers killed in last week's 
trailer park ambush. 
</P>
<P>
	Atascosa County Sheriff's Deputy Thomas Monse and Texas  
Department of Public Safety Trooper Terry Miller were buried. 
</P>
<P>
	Monse's widow, Mary Alice Monse, joked at the service that her  
husband sometimes called her ``a crybaby'' because she worried 
about him being hurt on the job. Monse, 31, was the first of the 
three officers to die from gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
	``The night I found this out, I said, 'I promise you I will be  
the strongest person you have ever seen,''' Mrs. Monse told 400 
mourners at St. Andrews Roman Catholic Church. ``'I will show you I 
can say goodbye to you, the way I want to say goodbye.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Monse recalled the couple's good and bad times, then spoke  
of her loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel so robbed,'' she said. ``This should not have ended  
this way. We should have died together when we were old. You should 
have walked your daughter down the aisle and been a grandfather.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a nearby cemetery, Monse was laid to rest in a gray metal  
casket among the hackberries and mesquites in a ceremony brimming 
with pageantry. 
</P>
<P>
	Later that day in Jourdanton, a few miles away, a crowd spilled  
into the parking lot of St. John's Lutheran Church to honor the 
37-year-old Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	In a eulogy for the slain trooper, Pastor Alston Kirk said  
Miller's last act of getting into his car and backing away from the 
scene may have saved other lawmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``In death, Terry gave life,'' Kirk told the crowd, which  
included about 400 uniformed officers from around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The shootings leave nine children fatherless, families shattered  
and police stunned. 
</P>
<P>
	``The loss of a lawman anywhere affects all of us because of our  
brotherhood,'' said Sgt. Mike Bonin of the Arizona Highway Patrol. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller and Monse were among the officers lured to a trailer park  
in Pleasanton, 25 miles south of San Antonio, by a bogus 911 call 
Tuesday night. When they arrived, 21-year-old Jeremiah Engleton 
fatally shot them and wounded two other officers before killing 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The funeral for the third officer, 32-year-old Atascosa County  
Sheriff's Deputy Mark Stephenson, was Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
