<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 08:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Revives Health Care Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE PLACID, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton stood in front  
of 500 nurses and reminded them of a debacle in her public life, 
the 1994 defeat of the health care reform initiative she directed. 
</P>
<P>
	Weird campaign strategy? Not so, advisers to her Senate campaign  
committee and others maintain. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Miringoff, head of Marist College's Institute for Public  
Opinion, said that with education and health care ranking as big 
issues with voters, the strategy may make perfect sense. 
</P>
<P>
	Miringoff said the Clinton camp seems to believe that she  
matches up well on those issues against her likely Republican 
opponent in next year's election, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are looking for contrasting issues,'' Miringoff said.  
</P>
<P>
	In fact, a majority of Mrs. Clinton's summertime ``listening  
tour'' events across New York state were held at health care 
facilities or educational institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Health care is an important issue for New Yorkers, and it will  
be an important issue in this campaign,'' Howard Wolfson, spokesman 
for Mrs. Clinton's political committee, said Friday, the day after 
her address to the New York State Nurses Association in Lake 
Placid. ``New Yorkers know that Hillary Clinton cares about 
improving health care, and they know that Rudy Giuliani doesn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, that's the crass politics of it. The first lady  
offers a somewhat more uplifting explanation of why she still cares 
about health care reform despite her congressional drubbing five 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the results of that effort, there are probably many who  
find it hard to understand why I would keep talking about health 
care,'' she said Thursday. ``The answer is simple. It's something 
I've been talking about and working on my entire adult life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Giuliani camp believes Mrs. Clinton is vulnerable on health  
care. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a legitimate issue,'' Giuliani political spokesman Bruce  
Teitelbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her record, if I can use that word, is going to be scrutinized  
very carefully -- not just what she says in speeches, but as it 
relates to ... what her position has been and what she's done,'' 
the Giuliani adviser said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was widely criticized for her handling of health  
care reform in 1994; some said she was pushing socialized medicine 
on America. On top of that, federal budget-balancing cuts approved 
in 1997 by Congress and her husband, President Clinton, hurt the 
state's health care facilities. Those are issues that could be used 
by the Giuliani camp against her. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's there, so she doesn't have much choice but to go out  
front on it,'' Miringoff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said Thursday the 1997 budget cuts went too far.  
</P>
<P>
	``These cuts ... have caused too much pain and are cutting into  
too much muscle and bone,'' the first lady said. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort appeared designed, in part, to inoculate her against  
attacks on that front, even if it was her husband and the GOP-led 
Congress that ordered the cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	The state -- and perhaps the first lady's campaign -- got a boost  
Friday when the federal government decided New York hospitals 
serving the poorest residents will not have to reimburse Washington 
nearly $1 billion in overpayments. 
</P>
<P>
	Miringoff thinks there are two other factors prompting Mrs.  
Clinton's embrace of changes in the health care system as a New 
York campaign issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, they can't focus on her roots in New York, so they  
have to shift the dialogue over to other things,'' he said. Mrs. 
Clinton has never lived or worked in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	And, according to the independent pollster, ``her strategy is  
going to be to nationalize the debate as much as possible'' in an 
attempt to tie Giuliani to Congress' conservative Republican 
leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, the Clinton camp has attacked Giuliani for not taking a  
public position on the current debate in Congress over giving 
patients more rights in dealing with their HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still 13 months away from the election,'' Teitelbaum  
said Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
