<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Calif. Quake Damage Limited  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The quake that jolted the Southwest  
early today had an intimidating magnitude of 7.0, but thanks to the 
remote location of its epicenter, major injuries and damage were 
avoided. The quake -- the most powerful in California since 1992 -- 
struck in the Mojave Desert, about 120 miles east of Los Angeles, 
and was felt in Las Vegas and as far away as Phoenix. Last month, a 
magnitude-7.2 quake rocked Taiwan, killing more than 2,300 people. 
In August, a 7.4 quake killed at least 17,000 people in Turkey. 

</P>
<P>
	West Bank-Gaza Link May Be Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- The opening of a land link between the West  
Bank and Gaza Strip is being delayed for a second time in two weeks 
because of disagreements over how to operate it, Palestinian and 
Israeli officials said Saturday. The passage was to have opened 
Sunday, allowing Palestinians for the first time to move relatively 
freely between the two Palestinian areas that lie on either side of 
Israel. However, the Israelis and Palestinians were unable to agree 
on the location of an office in the Gaza Strip that would hand out 
travel permits for the Palestinians. 

</P>
<P>
	Irene Threatening Carolinas  
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Hurricane Irene began a slow march  
up the East Coast today, slipping out of Florida after dumping 
heavy rain and knocking out power to more than a million people. 
The storm blamed for at least seven deaths was expected to hug the 
East Coast as it moved north and forecasters feared it could gain 
strength and dump several inches of rain on the flood-weary 
Carolinas through the weekend. A hurricane watch issued today 
stretched north to Cape Hatteras, N.C. The storm was packing winds 
of 80 mph. 

</P>
<P>
	New Pakistan Regime Sets Priorities  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistani army chief Pervaiz  
Musharraf canceled a promised television address Saturday that was 
expected to outline an interim government. Meanwhile, Pakistani 
army officers combed bank records and questioned travelers at 
airports after the new military regime made economic revival and 
the hunt for looted wealth its top priorities. The search for 
illicit assets was the first act of the regime, which ousted the 
elected government Tuesday, announced emergency rule and proclaimed 
Musharraf as the supreme leader. 

</P>
<P>
	Taliban Rejects U.N. Ultimatum  
</P>
<P>
	KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- Afghanistan's Taliban leaders rejected  
a U.N. ultimatum to surrender suspected terrorist Osama bin Laden 
and castigated the world body today for threatening sanctions. ``We 
will never give up Osama at any price,'' the Taliban's Foreign 
Minister Mullah Mohammed Hassan Akhund said in a statement. The 
U.N. Security Council yesterday decided to impose limited economic 
sanctions on the Taliban if it does not hand bin Laden over by Nov. 
14. ``No proof came from anyone, especially America, that Osama was 
involved in terrorist activities,'' Akhund said. 

</P>
<P>
	South Pole Doctor Rescued  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- Researchers bid an American  
doctor with breast cancer symptoms goodbye Saturday as a plane 
rescued her from their South Pole research station. The temperature 
was a relatively balmy 58 degrees below zero. Dr. Jerri Nielsen was 
inspected by physicians after the flight from the pole to McMurdo 
base on Antarctica's coast. Nielsen discovered a lump in her breast 
in June after the ultra-cold temperatures of the Antarctic winter 
had closed in, sealing off the research station and its inhabitants 
to the outside world. 

</P>
<P>
	S.C. Flag Spurs NAACP Tourism Boycott  
</P>
<P>
	LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) -- The NAACP's national board today approved  
a tourism boycott of South Carolina until the state removes the 
Confederate battle flag from the Statehouse dome. ``The 
ratification officially mobilizes all of our chapters and members 
to not visit or spend dollars in South Carolina until the flag is 
removed,'' said NAACP spokeswoman Sheila Douglas. More than $280 
million a year that black travelers spend in South Carolina could 
be at stake. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 17 Wisconsin Routs Indiana 59-0  
</P>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Ron Dayne ran for 167 of Wisconsin's  
school-record 705 yards of total offense as No. 17 Wisconsin 
steamrolled Indiana 59-0 today. Dayne, who had just 17 carries and 
sat out the entire second half, became the fourth player in 
Division I history to record four 1,000-yard rushing seasons. 
Wisconsin (5-2, 3-1) led 38-0 at halftime, didn't punt in the game 
and failed to score on just two drives. Indiana (3-4, 2-2) twice 
couldn't score inside Wisconsin's 20. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
