<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Army Faces Congo Mining Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni has  
reportedly ordered his troops in Congo to steer clear of mining 
deals, a move apparently aimed at easing rifts between forces 
trying to unseat Congo's president. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions among rival rebel groups and between their backers,  
Rwanda and Uganda, have stemmed from the battle for control of 
Congo's rich resources, said rebel leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba. 
His comments were broadcast Friday on state-run Radio Uganda. 
</P>
<P>
	Wamba, who was ousted in May as leader of the main rebel  
movement, the Rwandan-backed Congolese Rally for Democracy, said he 
was concerned that Rwandan authorities have not taken similar 
steps. 
</P>
<P>
	Rwanda denies its soldiers are involved in mineral deals or any  
other business in Congo. 
</P>
<P>
	Ugandan authorities could not be immediately reached for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebellion that began in August 1998 to oust President  
Laurent Kabila swept through the eastern third of Congo before a 
peace accord went into effect on Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	But infighting over rebel leadership and disputes between Rwanda  
and Uganda over how to end the war and for control of Congo's 
lucrative natural resources have strained relations between the two 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, Rwandan and Ugandan politicians have been  
meeting to patch up their damaged relations and have reportedly 
reached agreement to unite Congolese rebels into a single group, 
the Ugandan government-owned New Vision newspaper said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ugandans also back a third rebel group, the Movement for  
Congolese Liberation, headed by Jean-Pierre Bemba. His father, 
Bemba Saolona, is Kabila's minister of economy and industry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 18:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brush Fires Break Out in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELLA VISTA, Calif. (AP) -- Residents living near this rural  
Northern California town were hastily evacuated Saturday because of 
a fast-moving brush fire that grew from 3,000 to 15,000 acres in a 
single afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty to 70 homes and other structures had been consumed by the  
blaze, which broke out about 4:15 a.m. Saturday, in an area that 
experienced a similar brush fire just weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing left in this town,'' said California  
Department of Forestry spokeswoman Rose Wyckoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents in the town of Millville, Jones Valley and Palo Cedro  
had also been evacuated. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Wyckoff said the exact number of evacuees was not available.  
</P>
<P>
	The fire was consuming heavy timber in some areas and lighter  
grassy brush in others. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 firefighters were working the blaze, which was  
made more intense by warm temperatures and gusty winds over 25 mph. 
The cause of the fire was not known and there was no estimate of a 
time for containment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're praying for rain,'' said Ms. Wyckoff.  
</P>
<P>
	An evacuation center was set up at Anderson High School.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
