<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 14:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New L.A. Sports Arena Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Wearing a faded Lakers T-shirt and a bright  
grin, 16-year-old Nick Astrinakis walked outside after a brief tour 
Saturday of the new $375 million Staples Center pumping his arms in 
the air. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was great,'' said the diehard Lakers fan. ``It's huge, real  
state-of-the-art. I've never seen anything like it, I'm really 
excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His enthusiasm was shared by politicians and clergy who  
officially opened the downtown sports and entertainment center with 
a multi-denominational blessing, public tour and all-day, all-night 
street festival ending at 10 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Roman Catholic Cardinal Roger Mahony led the blessing ceremony,  
which mirrored the city's ethnic and religious diversity by 
including representatives from major faiths. 
</P>
<P>
	``By giving us rest and healthy recreation you refresh our weary  
bodies and minds,'' Mahony said during the blessing and 
ribbon-cutting ceremony. ``May it contribute to the enrichment of 
companionship and lead to new friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Richard Riordan said the privately funded center should be  
seen as a symbol of downtown revitalization efforts and a new era 
for the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we're sending a loud and clear message to the rest of  
the world,'' Riordan said. ``Los Angeles is still No. 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The venue will be the new home of the NBA's Lakers and Clippers,  
the NHL's Kings, and the Avengers, a new Arena Football League 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Staples Center will feature concerts. It will  
host the 42nd Grammy Awards in February and the 2000 Democratic 
National Convention in August. 
</P>
<P>
	State Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa said the new center  
was a good first step in rejuvenating downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's an understanding that we have to make downtown  
attractive,'' Villaraigosa said. ``I think today is important for 
that reason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Randon Caceres of Downey, brought his children to opening day to  
show his support for the home teams and for sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something they should experience,'' Caceres said.  
``Plus, I might not get another chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going to a game could be a struggle for the average sports fan.  
Single game regular admission prices for the Kings and Clippers 
range from $10 to $300, while tickets for the city's beloved Lakers 
range from $21 to $150. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be going to Lakers games,'' Caceres said. ``But I have a  
wife and kid, so I just go by myself.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
