<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio St.'s Awful Stretch Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- John Cooper was only half right when  
he said Ohio State couldn't beat this Penn State team at its best. 
</P>
<P>
	His punchless Buckeyes couldn't stop Penn State at its most  
inconsistent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nittany Lions sputtered time and again inside the 20, threw  
an interception, fumbled at their 1 and had two field goals 
blocked. Yet Ohio State still couldn't avoid a 23-10 defeat and the 
worst seven-game record in more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can't block and you can't tackle, then you're not going  
to beat a good football team,'' Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State (4-3 overall, 1-2 Big Ten) has lost three games for  
the first time since 1988, Cooper's first season. That year, the 
Buckeyes were 2-4 on the way to finishing 4-6-1. 
</P>
<P>
	And road games against nationally ranked Michigan and Michigan  
State still await. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Ohio State gave up 211 rushing yards to Eric McCoo,  
the first time a back had more than 200 yards since Curtis Enis' 
211 in Penn State's 31-27 victory in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State gave up 246 rushing yards, the most since Penn State  
ran for 316 that day two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State hadn't scored so few points since losing to Michigan  
13-9 in 1996 -- and the offense managed only a field goal. The 
defense turned Penn State's fumble into a TD. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shouldn't be that the defense scores more than the  
offense,'' linebacker Na'il Diggs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Bellisari ran for 38 yards and threw for 78. Reggie  
Germany caught three passes for 45 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the Ohio State offense was a no-show. Tailback  
Michael Wiley ran for just 18 yards on 10 carries. Ken-Yon Rambo 
had one catch for 5 yards. A team averaging 399 yards a game 
managed a measly 143. Bellisari was sacked eight times. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive lineman Tyson Walter said the Buckeyes were just  
confused. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just did everything wrong,'' Walter said. ``It was just an  
atrocious game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes can blame youth after losing its quarterback, its  
No. 2 runner, two wideouts and three defensive stars to graduation 
from last year's 11-1 team. 
</P>
<P>
	``That football team has a lot of talent,'' Penn State's Joe  
Paterno said. ``The only thing this Ohio State team doesn't have 
that they had last year is experience.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
