<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Quake Rocks Southern California  
</P>
<P>
	JOSHUA TREE, Calif. (AP) -- A 7.0-magnitude earthquake in the  
Mojave Desert shook millions awake in three Western states early 
today, derailing an Amtrak train, knocking out power to thousands, 
but causing no serious damage or injuries. The quake jolted 
gamblers out of bed in Las Vegas and shook buildings as far away as 
Phoenix and Tijuana, Mexico. Up to 90,000 utility customers lost 
power, mobile homes were knocked off pilings in the desert 
community of Ludlow and a highway bridge was cracked. With only a 
handful of injuries and no deaths, Californians credited location 
and luck for eluding catastrophe in the most powerful quake to hit 
the state since 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Ramsey Case May Get New Prosecutor  
</P>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Gov. Bill Owens will meet with Boulder  
District Attorney Alex Hunter Monday night to discuss the 
possibility of appointing a special prosecutor for the JonBenet 
Ramsey case, on of Hunter's advisors said. The grand jury 
investigation of the Ramsey case, launched by Hunter Sept. 15, 
1998, ended Wednesday without any indictments. Owens announced 
Wednesday that he would consider appointing a special prosecutor to 
review the case. A spokeswoman for Owens declined to reveal the 
time or location of the meeting. 

</P>
<P>
	SBC To Upgrade Internet Access  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- SBC Communications, the local phone company for  
the Southwest and Midwest, plans to spend billions of dollars more 
to bring robust Internet access to its customers sooner, according 
to an industry report. The company, which just completed its $73 
billion acquisition of rival baby Bell Ameritech, is expected to 
announce on Monday that it will invest up to $2.5 billion more in 
upgrading its local phone networks over the next three years, the 
investment firm Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. said in a report to its 
customers. 

</P>
<P>
	Washington Fund Raising Event Sets Record  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Republican presidential front-runner George W.  
Bush helped raise more than $400,000 in Washington State today at a 
GOP fund raising event staged in America's newest and most 
expensive ballpark, Safeco Field. The sum is the largest single 
fund-raising event in the state's history. Bush lent his starpower 
and fund raising prowess to Sen. Slade Gorton, the state GOP, and 
the National Republican Senatorial Committee. The move is part of a 
new Bush strategy to cement his relations with congressional 
incumbents and organizations in key battleground states, Bush 
senior advisers said. 

</P>
<P>
	N.C. Declares Emergency As Irene Nears  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) -- Gov. Jim Hunt declared a state of  
emergency today as hurricane Irene rumbled up the East Coast, 
taking aim at flood-weary North Carolina. Officials considered 
evacuations and warned that it wouldn't take much rain to push 
rivers in the eastern part of the state back above flood stages. 
Irene's 80-mph winds also could threaten camper villages populated 
by people left homeless by the floods. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, Giuliani Slip in Polls  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Whether or not they will be able to cast a  
vote for next year's Senate race in New York, Americans are looking 
less favorably upon anticipated candidates Rudolph Giuliani and 
Hillary Rodham Clinton, according to a poll released today. The CBS 
News poll found that 16 percent of those questioned nationwide 
earlier this month gave Giuliani, New York City's Republican mayor, 
an ``unfavorable'' rating. Six percent found him unfavorable in a 
March 1998 poll. As for Mrs. Clinton, 36 percent of those polled 
this month had unfavorable impressions of her, up from 20 percent 
in January 1999. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Spank Yankees 13-1  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox routed the New York Yankees  
13-1 tonight at Fenway Park. Boston's Pedro Martinez dominated for 
seven shutout innings while the Red Sox roughed up Roger Clemens in 
sending the Yankees to their most lopsided loss in postseason 
history, in Game 3 of the AL Championship Series. Martinez set a 
Red Sox postseason record by striking out 12 and allowed just two 
singles. Game 4 will be tomorrow night with Bret Saberhagen 
starting against New York's Andy Pettitte. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 20 Purdue Upsets No. 5 Mich. St.  
</P>
<P>
	WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- Twentieth-ranked Purdue beat No. 5  
Michigan State 52-28 today with Drew Brees throwing five touchdown 
passes in the first half, including three to Chris Daniels, and 
running for one in the second half. Purdue (5-2, 2-2 Big Ten) built 
a 35-14 lead by halftime as Brees completed 23-of-33 for 344 yards. 
It was Michigan State's first loss of the year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
</P>
