<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Damage Limited by Location </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The quake that jolted the Southwest  
early Saturday had an intimidating magnitude of 7.0. But, thanks to 
the remote location of its epicenter, it wasn't even close to being 
a disaster like Turkey, Taiwan or Northridge. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake -- the most powerful in California since 1992 -- struck  
in the Mojave Desert, about 120 miles east of Los Angeles, and was 
felt in Las Vegas and as far away as Phoenix. There were no reports 
of major injuries or damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ground shaking was very strong at the epicenter and along  
the fault rupture,'' said Kate Hutton, a seismologist at the 
California Institute of Technology. ``If it had been in a populated 
area, it could have caused significant damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the largest quake to rock California since 1992, when a  
magnitude-7.3 tremor struck in the same desert near Landers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, a magnitude-7.2 quake rocked Taiwan, killing more  
than 2,300 people and causing an estimated $9.2 billion in damage. 
In August, a 7.4 quake killed at least 17,000 people in Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1994 Northridge quake in Los Angeles registered 6.7, killed  
72 people and caused $25 billion in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	In those cases, the faults ruptured either directly under or  
near populated areas. Saturday's most intense shaking occurred in 
open desert where there are more Joshua trees and tortoises than 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	``The level of shaking is comparable to what was experienced in  
Northridge,'' said Lucy Jones, scientist-in-charge of the U.S. 
Geological Survey office in Pasadena. ``The good news is that there 
are fewer people out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earthquakes are caused by the sudden release of pressure that  
builds up when sections of the Earth lock together deep beneath the 
surface. From the fault rupture, where the rock snaps, sound-like 
waves speed through the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Layers of sediment and rock below the surface can amplify or  
mute the destructive waves. That is why pockets of heavy damage are 
sometimes surrounded by areas with relatively little in large 
quakes near metropolitan areas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Loma Prieta earthquake that struck 10 years ago Sunday,  
Oakland sustained heavy shaking and damage even though the 
epicenter was located about 60 miles south. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Saturday's quake, the distance muted the violent shaking  
felt by the few people who live near the epicenter, seismologists 
said. In west Los Angeles -- nearly 150 miles from the epicenter -- 
the shaking was a sickening slow roll not unlike riding in a boat 
on the ocean surf. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the waves are lost as it gets farther away,'' Hutton  
said. ``The quake gets weaker. It becomes more of rolling 
earthquake with the greater distance. A person sitting on top of 
the fault probably felt a much sharper motion than what we felt in 
L.A.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the shaking also seems to last longer for people who live  
farther away from the epicenter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not all waves travel at the same speed -- some waves are slower  
than others,'' she said. ``Because of the variation in speed, it 
feels long.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 03:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Rocks Los Angeles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A magnitude-7.0 earthquake struck Southern  
California today, a long rumbling that shook buildings from 
downtown Los Angeles to Las Vegas. There were no immediate reports 
of damage or injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a bad one. Things are bouncing around all over. But  
we are all right. I have to go and call the kids,'' Lucille Manning 
said from her home in Chino, 40 miles south of Landers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucy Jones of the California Institute of Technology said the  
quake measured 7.0. It struck about 3 a.m. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
