<DOCNO> APW19991016.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 00:20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Water Districts Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Ending years of negotiations, Southern  
California water districts have reached a landmark deal to divide 
water from the Colorado River to ensure that they no longer take 
more than their fair share. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative plan struck Friday will be voted on next week.  
</P>
<P>
	The six other Western states that draw from the river had  
pressured Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt to do something about 
California continually taking more than its share. In response, he 
set a Friday deadline for the districts to agree on a way to stay 
within their allotment or risk immediate loss of their surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the Metropolitan Water District, the Imperial  
Irrigation District and the Coachella Valley Water District 
wouldn't discuss the specific terms of the agreement, but confirmed 
that an accord should be signed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``All sides appear to be happy,'' Coachella spokesman Dennis  
Mahr said. ``Hopefully, there's a settlement, but the lawyers are 
still going over the language'' in the more than 50-page document. 
</P>
<P>
	Imperial board president Bruce Kuhn said he was optimistic that  
all the boards would approve the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``After all these months of intense negotiations, that would be  
the icing on the cake,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The districts, along with the San Diego County Water Authority,  
spent the past three days in marathon sessions to reach an 
agreement rather than face intervention from Gov. Gray Davis or 
Babbitt. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1922 agreement, California is assured 4.4 million  
acre-feet of water a year from the Colorado River. However, only 
550,000 acre-feet is budgeted for the heavily populated coastal 
strip and inland regions. 
</P>
<P>
	An acre-foot is about 326,000 gallons, or enough water for a  
family of four for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past few years, Metropolitan, which owns the aqueduct  
that supplies water to 16 million people in Southern California, 
has been taking as much 5.2 million acre-feet to meet demand. 
</P>
<P>
	To reduce the region's reliance on the surpluses, the districts  
had to agree on how to share the allotment, meaning some districts 
had to give water to others; who would retain the rights; how much 
each district would pay for the water and conservation programs; 
and how the districts would share costs of an environmental impact 
review for the Imperial-San Diego water transfer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 16:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rocket Rocketed Out of Fenway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Can't win the big one, that's what they say here  
about Roger Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Couldn't win it during 11 seasons with the Boston Red Sox, can't  
win it now with the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	He has five Cy Young Awards, more than any other man, alive or  
dead. But no World Series rings, the only gem he says he ever 
really wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	From Clemens' very first batter Saturday, it was a party at  
Fenway Park, and he was the pinata as Red Sox fans celebrated a 
13-1 victory that pulled them to 2-1 in the AL Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	They booed when he warmed up in the bullpen, a passionate angry  
roar directed toward one of their own who had defected and joined 
their enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	They booed again when he walked out to the mound, already deep  
in shadows as brilliant autumn sunshine lighted up the old 
grandstands, filled with fans longing for their team's first World 
Series title since 1918. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rog-ger, Rog-er'' they sang again and again, a slow singsong  
designed to make sure he appreciated the magnitude of their 
disdain. 
</P>
<P>
	Just two pitches in, the booing abruptly ended, replaced by  
cheers as Jose Offerman's leadoff drive sailed over the head of 
Paul O'Neill in right, caroming off the low fence and back toward 
the infield as Offerman sped to third. 
</P>
<P>
	Five pitches later, John Valentin lofted the ball toward the  
Green Monster and out it went, over the 37-foot fence and into the 
23-foot screen, even deeper than Bucky Dent's famous drive 21 years 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fans were still walking in, and already Clemens was behind  
2-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rog-ger, Rog-er,'' they kept singing as he finally retired the  
side. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in the second came a double by Trot Nixon, a single by  
Offerman, an RBI grounder by Valentin and a run-scoring double by 
Nomar Garciaparra. By then, Hideki Irabu was starting to warm up in 
the bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Stanley started the third with a single, and Clemens threw  
a first-pitch strike to Brian Daubach, his 61st pitch of the 
afternoon. It turned out to be his last. 
</P>
<P>
	As Clemens gave manager Joe Torre the ball and walked off the  
mound, back to the Yankees' dugout on the third-base side, the fans 
started booing, wanting to leave him with the sound of their hate 
in his ears. 
</P>
<P>
	To them, the 247-134 regular-season record and 3,316 strikeouts  
don't matter. They remember that he went 1-2 in nine postseason 
starts for Boston, and that new hero Pedro Martinez, who struck out 
12 and allowed just two hits in seven shutout innings Saturday, 
already is 3-0 in his career during the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, what had happened suddenly struck them. They started  
cheering for Boston, a loud release that reverberated out to 
Kenmore Square and on to the Back Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens' line read: five runs, six hits, just two innings  
pitched. By the seventh inning, when the score reached 13-0, the 
chant had changed to, ``Where is Roger?'' 
</P>
<P>
	For once, Red Sox fans dreamed the dream and it came true.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 14:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada GM Plant Denounces Outscoring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Plans by General Motors of Canada Ltd. to end  
production at the St. Therese, Quebec, assembly plant and outsource 
other work could lead to a walk-out by Canadian Auto Workers, union 
president Buzz Hargrove said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outsourcing positions they have on the table will cause a  
strike,'' Hargrove said at a Toronto news conference. ``Under no 
circumstances are we going to allow outsourcing when we have 
insecurity with workers at St. Therese and other plants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The CAW has set a midnight Tuesday deadline to reach an  
agreement with GM. During 1996 contract talks, the CAW struck GM's 
Oshawa, Ontario, assembly plant, idling some U.S. parts and 
assembly plants. 
</P>
<P>
	A contract with GM is expected to closely model agreements  
already reached with Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Those call for a 3 percent wage increase in each year of a  
three-year package, a $1,000 (Canadian) signing bonus, an improved 
retirement package and other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said in July that the future of the St. Therese plant  
and GM plans to outsource work would be key issues in this year's 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowered demand for the Chevrolet Cameros and Pontiac Firebirds  
produced at St. Therese has raised speculation that the plant might 
be closed. GM has said it will cease production of the cars there 
in September 2002, and nothing is scheduled to replace that line, 
Hargrove said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM officials in Detroit and Ontario could not be immediately  
reached for comment Saturday. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 08:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Treaty a Political Football </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With President Clinton accusing Senate  
Republicans of reckless, blatant partisanship, Democrats are trying 
to stir the rejection of the nuclear test ban treaty into a 2000 
campaign issue. 
</P>
<P>
	But even Clinton had to acknowledge that it may not work. He had  
said earlier that the test ban would not be a huge issue either 
way, and the polls indicate that probably is so. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the end of the Cold War, foreign policy concerns have  
slipped down the list of voter priorities, dominated by issues at 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the Senate ``clearly disregarded the views of the  
American people who have consistently and strongly supported this 
treaty ever since it was first pursued by Presidents Eisenhower and 
Kennedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eisenhower proposed a nuclear test ban in 1958, in a different  
world, challenging the old Soviet Union to agree to stop testing. 
Kennedy signed, and the Senate approved, a limited test ban treaty 
in 1963, barring all but underground nuclear tests by the United 
States and the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty Clinton signed in 1996 and lost in the Senate would  
extend an international ban on atmospheric tests to underground 
testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican opponents said the ban couldn't be enforced, and was  
dangerous to future U.S. security. They voted it down 51 to 48 on 
Wednesday, with four Republicans in favor. Ratification would have 
required a two-thirds majority, 67 votes, and Clinton never was 
close to that strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a political deal and I hope it will get the treatment  
from the American people it richly deserves,'' the president said 
after the vote he knew he would lose. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also said that the treaty will ultimately be ratified.  
But it obviously won't happen on his watch, with Republicans in 
55-to-45 Senate control through 2000, and therefore in command of 
what is brought up for action. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Democrats tried to challenge that GOP prerogative, and  
delay action on the treaty, they lost, on straight party lines. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't kill the treaty outright. Vice President Al Gore  
said rejection was ``an act of almost breathtaking 
irresponsibility.'' He then made it the subject of his first 
campaign television commercial. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe in my heart this vote does not speak for the  
American people,'' the vice president says in the ad. ``So why 
don't we do something about it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He asked voters for their support in his campaign, and for a  
mandate to send the treaty back to the Senate in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Rival Democrat Bill Bradley also favors the treaty.  
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner for 2000, is  
opposed, as are the other GOP candidates. But Bush says he would 
continue the voluntary moratorium on U.S. testing that has been in 
effect since 1992. Britain, France, Russia and, since 1996, China 
also are refraining from testing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never before has a serious treaty involving nuclear weapons  
been handled in such a reckless and ultimately partisan way,'' 
Clinton said. ``This issue should be beyond politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But campaign politics is the only arena in which the Democrats  
can pursue it now. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who started the  
process that led to rejection and then couldn't control it, said he 
doubts they can make a winning campaign issue of the treaty because 
Americans know it is flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	Public opinion polls do show overwhelming support for a treaty  
prohibiting nuclear weapons test explosions worldwide -- 82 percent, 
according to a 1999 survey the Democrats cite. But in issue 
surveys, foreign policy in general is cited by only about 5 percent 
of potential voters as a top priority, and the issue of nuclear 
weapons ranks even lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said at his news conference on Thursday that he never  
wanted the treaty to be a political issue, but it might become one 
now that the Republicans have blocked it. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also acknowledged that Americans aren't worried about the  
nuclear threat as they were in the Cold War era. So he said it may 
or may not have an impact on the campaign. He wants it to, although 
he minimized the prospect earlier when he was trying to get the 
Senate vote delayed, to avoid the defeat he knew was coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not going to be a huge issue in the election one way  
or the other,'' Clinton said on Oct. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 13:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Japan Insurance Cos. To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Three major Japanese insurance companies have  
agreed to bring their operations together by 2001, a major Japanese 
business daily reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a single holding company, Mitsui Marine and Fire Insurance  
Co., Nippon Fire and Marine Insurance Co. and Koa Fire and Marine 
Insurance Co. will tie up their damage investigation divisions and 
computer information systems, the Nihon Keizai Shimbun said. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance will produce the biggest Japanese non-life  
insurance group in terms of assets, overtaking Tokio Marine and 
Fire Insurance Co, the report said. Mitsui is the third largest, 
while Nippon is fifth and Koa eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance will fall short of a full-fledged merger, but the  
companies will cooperate in underwriting insurance policies as well 
as in asset management, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	As competition increases, non-life insurers are likely to be  
pressed to cut premiums. The three insurers hope to move ahead with 
cost-cutting by joining forces, the Nihon Keizai said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0208 </DOCNO>
