<P>
	Layers of sediment and rock below the surface can amplify or  
mute the destructive waves. That is why pockets of heavy damage are 
sometimes surrounded by areas with relatively little in large 
quakes near metropolitan areas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Loma Prieta earthquake that struck 10 years ago Sunday,  
Oakland sustained heavy shaking and damage even though the 
epicenter was located about 60 miles south. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Saturday's quake, the distance muted the violent shaking  
felt by the few people who live near the epicenter, seismologists 
said. In west Los Angeles -- nearly 150 miles from the epicenter -- 
the shaking was a sickening slow roll not unlike riding in a boat 
on the ocean surf. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the waves are lost as it gets farther away,'' Hutton  
said. ``The quake gets weaker. It becomes more of rolling 
earthquake with the greater distance. A person sitting on top of 
the fault probably felt a much sharper motion than what we felt in 
L.A.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the shaking also seems to last longer for people who live  
farther away from the epicenter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not all waves travel at the same speed -- some waves are slower  
than others,'' she said. ``Because of the variation in speed, it 
feels long.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991016.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-16 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lou Holtz Returns to Arkansas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Lou Holtz was back on the sidelines at  
War Memorial Stadium on Saturday night, only he was on the east 
side -- the visitors' side. 
</P>
<P>
	During his seven years (1977-83) as Arkansas' head coach, the  
Razorbacks were 21-3 in Little Rock. This time around, he was 
coaching winless South Carolina, which lost again 48-14. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans had little reaction to his return. Maybe they  
remembered the magic he worked in 1977, or maybe it was a touch of 
compassion for a former ally who inherited a Gamecocks program with 
a losing streak that dated to Sept. 12, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A sign on a truck pronounced, ``Cock-A-Doodle Lou.''  
</P>
<P>
	``The people here were fine,'' Holtz said after the game. ``I  
have no problem with that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got beat by a fine football team,'' he said. ``It doesn't  
matter where it was, here or anywhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About a half-hour before the game, Holtz and Arkansas coach  
Houston Nutt met on the Arkansas side of the field, embracing at 
the 50-yard line. Nutt was a graduate assistant under Holtz at 
Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	When Holtz arrived at Arkansas, he was a wispy, wisecracking  
coach disillusioned with the NFL who replaced Frank Broyles and his 
Georgia drawl. In Broyles' final five years, only once did Arkansas 
win more than six games. In 1976, the Razorbacks were 5-5-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz's first team won 10 and earned a spot in the prestigious  
Orange Bowl against Oklahoma. The Sooners were unbeaten and ranked 
No. 2, and Arkansas was a 17-point underdog until Holtz suspended 
three players. After that, the game was off the boards in Las 
Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz spotted a problem with Oklahoma's nose guard, and his game  
plan made running back Roland Sales look like an All-American as 
Arkansas won 31-6. 
</P>
<P>
	A few days ago, Holtz said he remembered virtually every play of  
that game but added, ``Thank goodness, it wasn't a best of seven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz also said he wouldn't be emotional about his return to  
Arkansas, but that the walk through at War Memorial would trigger 
some memories -- including 34-0 over Houston in 1977 and 17-14 over 
Texas two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	After Friday's trip to the stadium, Holtz said Arkansas still  
``has the best police escorts in the country'' 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of former players talked with him at the stadium and  
1979 quarterback Kevin Scanlon said his stomach did a couple of 
flips when he heard Holtz holler at one of his South Carolina 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Holtz took Arkansas to six straight bowl games -- the first time  
that happened in school history. His humor landed him a guest spot 
on the Tonight Show with Johnny Carson, but he was also gracious 
enough to feed media members at his home after Fayetteville games. 
</P>
<P>
	He left Arkansas in December 1983 and there are myriad theories  
about why, including recruiting shortcomings and his failure to put 
together a top-notch staff. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end, the school said he was ``burned out'' on football.  
Less than a week later, he was hired on as head coach at Minnesota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
